        $places = [
            // ==================== JAPAN (City IDs 1-3) ====================
            // Tokyo (id: 1)
            ['city_id' => 1, 'name' => 'Senso-ji Temple', 'description' => 'Senso-ji is Tokyo\'s oldest and most significant Buddhist temple, located in Asakusa. Founded in 645 AD, the temple is dedicated to Kannon, the goddess of mercy. Visitors enter through the Kaminarimon (Thunder Gate) with its famous giant red lantern, then walk along Nakamise-dori, a shopping street with traditional snacks and souvenirs. The main hall and the five-story pagoda are architectural highlights. The temple is especially beautiful during cherry blossom season and New Year celebrations, when millions visit for hatsumode (first shrine visit of the year).', 'localisation' => '35.7147, 139.7967', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1536098561742-ca998e48cbcc?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 1, 'name' => 'Shibuya Crossing', 'description' => 'Shibuya Crossing is the world\'s busiest pedestrian crossing, famous for its organized chaos as hundreds of people cross from all directions when the traffic lights turn red. The crossing is best viewed from the second-floor Starbucks or the surrounding buildings. It has become a symbol of Tokyo\'s energy and modernity, featured in numerous films including "Lost in Translation" and "Fast and Furious: Tokyo Drift." The crossing is surrounded by giant video screens and neon signs, creating a quintessentially Tokyo experience. Nearby, you can see the statue of Hachiko, the loyal dog who waited for his owner at the station every day for nine years after his owner\'s death.', 'localisation' => '35.6595, 139.7005', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1542051841852-5f4f2a35b29c?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 1, 'name' => 'Tokyo Tower', 'description' => 'Tokyo Tower is a communications and observation tower inspired by the Eiffel Tower, standing 333 meters tall. Painted in international orange and white, it has been a symbol of Tokyo\'s post-war rebirth since its completion in 1958. The tower offers two observation decks: the Main Observatory at 150 meters and the Top Deck at 250 meters, providing panoramic views of Tokyo, including the Imperial Palace, Rainbow Bridge, and on clear days, Mount Fuji. The tower\'s base houses FootTown, featuring shops, restaurants, an aquarium, and a wax museum. The tower is beautifully illuminated at night, changing colors for different seasons and events.', 'localisation' => '35.6586, 139.7454', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1540959733332-eab4deabeeaf?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Kyoto (id: 2)
            ['city_id' => 2, 'name' => 'Fushimi Inari Shrine', 'description' => 'Fushimi Inari Shrine is the most important of thousands of shrines dedicated to Inari, the Shinto god of rice, sake, and prosperity. The shrine is famous for its thousands of vibrant red torii gates that form a network of trails leading up Mount Inari. The hike to the summit takes about 2-3 hours and passes through smaller shrines, cemeteries, and beautiful forest paths. The torii gates are donated by individuals and companies seeking good fortune, with donor names inscribed on the back. The shrine is especially atmospheric early in the morning or at dusk. Foxes, considered Inari\'s messengers, are featured throughout the shrine in statues and motifs.', 'localisation' => '34.9671, 135.7727', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1493976040374-85c8e12f0c0e?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 2, 'name' => 'Kinkaku-ji Golden Pavilion', 'description' => 'Kinkaku-ji, officially named Rokuon-ji, is one of Kyoto\'s most iconic Zen Buddhist temples. The top two floors of this three-story pavilion are completely covered in gold leaf, reflecting beautifully in the pond below. Originally built in 1397 as a retirement villa for Shogun Ashikaga Yoshimitsu, it was converted into a temple after his death. The temple has been burned down multiple times, most recently in 1950 by a mentally disturbed monk, an event that inspired Yukio Mishima\'s novel "The Temple of the Golden Pavilion." The current structure was rebuilt in 1955. The temple grounds include beautiful gardens, a tea house, and the Sekkatei Teahouse, where visitors can enjoy matcha tea.', 'localisation' => '35.0394, 135.7292', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1493976040374-85c8e12f0c0e?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 2, 'name' => 'Arashiyama Bamboo Grove', 'description' => 'The Arashiyama Bamboo Grove is one of Kyoto\'s most photographed sights, featuring a stunning path through towering bamboo stalks that sway in the wind, creating a unique rustling sound. The grove is located in the Arashiyama district, near the famous Togetsukyo Bridge. The main path is only about 500 meters long but offers a surreal, otherworldly atmosphere. It\'s best visited early in the morning or late afternoon to avoid crowds. The grove is part of a larger area that includes Tenryu-ji Temple (a UNESCO World Heritage site), the Okochi Sanso Villa, and the Monkey Park Iwatayama on the opposite hill.', 'localisation' => '35.0167, 135.6682', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1624298357141-67f9b4fbb05f?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Okinawa (id: 3)
            ['city_id' => 3, 'name' => 'Shurijo Castle', 'description' => 'Shurijo Castle is a UNESCO World Heritage site and the former palace of the Ryukyu Kingdom, which ruled Okinawa from the 15th to 19th centuries. The castle features a unique blend of Chinese, Japanese, and indigenous Ryukyuan architecture, with its distinctive red-tiled roofs and stone walls. The main hall (Seiden) was the center of royal ceremonies and politics. The castle was almost completely destroyed during the Battle of Okinawa in 1945 but has been meticulously reconstructed. The castle grounds offer beautiful views of Naha city and the East China Sea. The castle is also famous for its role in Ryukyuan performing arts, including traditional dances and music performances.', 'localisation' => '26.2174, 127.7186', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1545569341-9eb8b30979d9?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 3, 'name' => 'Cape Manzamo', 'description' => 'Cape Manzamo is a dramatic cliff formation on Okinawa\'s west coast, known for its unique shape resembling an elephant trunk and stunning ocean views. The name "Manzamo" means "a platform for 10,000 people," referring to the large grassy area on top of the cliff. The limestone cliffs were formed over millions of years by erosion. The cape offers spectacular sunset views over the East China Sea and is particularly beautiful in winter when humpback whales can sometimes be seen offshore. The surrounding area features walking trails, souvenir shops, and restaurants serving local Okinawan cuisine. Cape Manzamo is one of Okinawa\'s most photographed natural attractions.', 'localisation' => '26.5036, 127.8239', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1545569341-9eb8b30979d9?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 3, 'name' => 'Churaumi Aquarium', 'description' => 'The Churaumi Aquarium is one of the world\'s largest and most impressive aquariums, located within the Ocean Expo Park in northern Okinawa. The aquarium\'s main attraction is the Kuroshio Sea tank, one of the largest aquarium tanks in the world, holding 7,500 cubic meters of water. The tank features whale sharks, manta rays, and hundreds of other marine species, with a massive acrylic viewing panel that makes visitors feel like they\'re underwater. Other exhibits include the Coral Sea tank (with living coral), the Deep Sea tank (featuring bioluminescent creatures), and the Manatee Center. The aquarium also offers shark feeding shows and dolphin performances. "Churaumi" means "beautiful sea" in Okinawan dialect.', 'localisation' => '26.6948, 127.8765', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1545569341-9eb8b30979d9?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // ==================== ITALY (City IDs 4-6) ====================
            // Rome (id: 4)
            ['city_id' => 4, 'name' => 'Colosseum', 'description' => 'The Colosseum, also known as the Flavian Amphitheatre, is the largest ancient amphitheater ever built and one of the greatest works of Roman engineering. Constructed between 72-80 AD, it could hold up to 80,000 spectators who gathered to watch gladiatorial contests, animal hunts, and even mock sea battles (naumachiae). Despite earthquake damage and stone-robbers over the centuries, the Colosseum remains an iconic symbol of Imperial Rome. Visitors can explore the arena floor, the underground hypogeum where animals and gladiators awaited combat, and the upper tiers with spectacular views of Rome. The Colosseum is also associated with early Christian martyrs, and the Pope leads a Good Friday procession there. A must-see for any visitor to Rome.', 'localisation' => '41.8902, 12.4922', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1552832230-c0197dd311b5?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 4, 'name' => 'Vatican City', 'description' => 'Vatican City is the smallest independent state in the world, both by area (44 hectares) and population (about 800). It serves as the spiritual and administrative center of the Roman Catholic Church and the residence of the Pope. Despite its size, the Vatican is home to extraordinary art and architecture, including St. Peter\'s Basilica (the largest church in the world), the Sistine Chapel with Michelangelo\'s ceiling and The Last Judgment, and the Vatican Museums, which contain one of the world\'s greatest art collections. Visitors can attend Papal audiences (on Wednesdays) and Angelus prayers (on Sundays). The Swiss Guard, in their colorful Renaissance uniforms, protect the Pope. A visit to the Vatican is a highlight of any trip to Rome.', 'localisation' => '41.9029, 12.4534', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1552832230-c0197dd311b5?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 4, 'name' => 'Trevi Fountain', 'description' => 'The Trevi Fountain is the largest Baroque fountain in Rome and one of the most famous fountains in the world. Designed by Nicola Salvi and completed by Giuseppe Pannini in 1762, the fountain depicts Oceanus (god of all water) riding a shell-shaped chariot pulled by sea horses led by tritons. Legend has it that throwing a coin over your left shoulder into the fountain ensures your return to Rome. An estimated 3,000 euros are thrown into the fountain daily, which is collected and donated to Catholic charities. The fountain is spectacularly illuminated at night and has been featured in numerous films, most famously Federico Fellini\'s "La Dolce Vita" (1960) and "Three Coins in the Fountain" (1954).', 'localisation' => '41.9009, 12.4833', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1552832230-c0197dd311b5?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Venice (id: 5)
            ['city_id' => 5, 'name' => 'St. Mark\'s Square', 'description' => 'St. Mark\'s Square (Piazza San Marco) is the main public square of Venice and one of the world\'s most beautiful urban spaces. Napoleon called it "the drawing room of Europe." The square is dominated by St. Mark\'s Basilica, a masterpiece of Italo-Byzantine architecture with its golden mosaics and the famous bronze horses (now inside the museum). The Campanile (bell tower) offers spectacular views of Venice and the lagoon. The Doge\'s Palace, connected to the basilica, was the seat of Venetian government. The square is also home to the Procuratie buildings (housing offices and cafes) and the Torre dell\'Orologio (clock tower with moving figures). The square floods during high tide (acqua alta), creating beautiful reflections. It\'s the heart of Venetian life and a must-visit.', 'localisation' => '45.4343, 12.3388', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1514890547357-a9ee288728e0?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 5, 'name' => 'Grand Canal', 'description' => 'The Grand Canal is Venice\'s main waterway, winding through the city in a giant S-shape for about 3.8 kilometers. It is lined with over 170 magnificent buildings, many of which were palaces (palazzi) built between the 13th and 18th centuries. The best way to experience the canal is by taking a vaporetto (water bus) or, for a more romantic experience, a gondola. Highlights along the canal include the Rialto Bridge (the oldest bridge across the canal), the Ca\' d\'Oro (Golden House) with its Gothic facade, the Peggy Guggenheim Collection, and the Basilica of Santa Maria della Salute. The canal is especially beautiful at sunset when the buildings glow in golden light.', 'localisation' => '45.4408, 12.3300', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1514890547357-a9ee288728e0?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 5, 'name' => 'Rialto Bridge', 'description' => 'The Rialto Bridge (Ponte di Rialto) is the oldest and most famous of the four bridges spanning Venice\'s Grand Canal. The current stone bridge, designed by Antonio da Ponte, was completed in 1591 after a design competition (Michelangelo was a competitor). It features a single arch and a covered walkway with two rows of shops. The bridge has become a symbol of Venice and offers stunning views of the Grand Canal. The surrounding Rialto area has been the commercial heart of Venice since the 11th century, with a famous market that still operates today. The bridge is particularly beautiful at sunrise when it\'s less crowded, and at sunset when the light reflects on the water.', 'localisation' => '45.4385, 12.3359', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1514890547357-a9ee288728e0?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Amalfi Coast (id: 6)
            ['city_id' => 6, 'name' => 'Path of the Gods', 'description' => 'The Path of the Gods (Sentiero degli Dei) is a spectacular hiking trail along the Amalfi Coast, offering some of the most breathtaking coastal views in the world. The trail runs about 7.8 kilometers between the towns of Agerola (Bomerano) and Nocelle (above Positano). The path was originally a mule track connecting ancient settlements. The hike takes about 3-4 hours and offers stunning views of the Mediterranean Sea, the islands of Capri and Ischia, and the dramatic Amalfi coastline. The trail is at its most beautiful in spring when wildflowers bloom. The name comes from the belief that the views are so beautiful they must have been created by gods.', 'localisation' => '40.6280, 14.5550', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1523699601010-2b956a86752c?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 6, 'name' => 'Amalfi Cathedral', 'description' => 'Amalfi Cathedral (Duomo di Amalfi) is a stunning 9th-century Roman Catholic cathedral in the heart of Amalfi, dedicated to Apostle Saint Andrew. The cathedral features a striking Arab-Norman architectural style, with a beautiful striped facade, a bronze door cast in Constantinople, and a 13th-century bell tower. The interior houses a crypt containing the remains of Saint Andrew, which were brought from Constantinople during the Fourth Crusade. The cathedral museum (Museo Diocesano) displays sacred art, manuscripts, and the "Treasure of Amalfi." The Cloister of Paradise (Chiostro del Paradiso) is a tranquil Moorish-style courtyard with sarcophagi and gardens. The cathedral is particularly impressive when illuminated at night.', 'localisation' => '40.6345, 14.6027', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1523699601010-2b956a86752c?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 6, 'name' => 'Fiordo di Furore', 'description' => 'Fiordo di Furore is a hidden fjord on the Amalfi Coast, created by the Schiato stream carving through the mountains to the sea. The fjord is nestled between the towns of Furore and Conca dei Marini. A high arched bridge spans the fjord, and a small pebble beach sits at the water\'s edge. The beach is often called the "beach of love" and has been used as a setting in Italian films. The fjord is surrounded by colorful fishermen\'s houses clinging to the cliffs. It\'s one of the Amalfi Coast\'s most photographed spots, especially when the sun creates beautiful light effects on the water. The fjord can be reached by descending a long staircase from the bridge.', 'localisation' => '40.6211, 14.5542', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1523699601010-2b956a86752c?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // ==================== THAILAND (City IDs 7-9) ====================
            // Bangkok (id: 7)
            ['city_id' => 7, 'name' => 'Grand Palace', 'description' => 'The Grand Palace is the most famous landmark in Bangkok, a spectacular complex of royal buildings, temples, and courtyards that served as the official residence of the Kings of Siam (and later Thailand) from 1782 to 1925. The palace is still used for royal ceremonies and state functions. The complex covers 218,000 square meters and includes over 100 buildings. The most famous building is Wat Phra Kaew (Temple of the Emerald Buddha), which houses the Emerald Buddha, a highly revered statue carved from a single block of jade. The palace architecture is a stunning blend of Thai, European, and Chinese influences, with intricate details, golden spires, and colorful murals. Dress code is strictly enforced (no shorts, sleeveless tops, or flip-flops).', 'localisation' => '13.7500, 100.4915', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1552465011-b4e21bf6e79a?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 7, 'name' => 'Wat Arun Temple of Dawn', 'description' => 'Wat Arun, also known as the Temple of Dawn, is one of Bangkok\'s most iconic landmarks, located on the west bank of the Chao Phraya River. The temple\'s main feature is its 79-meter-high central prang (Khmer-style tower), decorated with millions of colorful porcelain pieces that sparkle in the sun. The porcelain originally came from Chinese ships that used it as ballast. The tower represents Mount Meru, the center of the universe in Buddhist cosmology. Visitors can climb the steep steps for beautiful views of the river and the Grand Palace. The temple is named after Aruna, the Hindu god of dawn, and is most beautiful at sunrise and sunset when the light makes the porcelain glow.', 'localisation' => '13.7437, 100.4887', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1552465011-b4e21bf6e79a?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 7, 'name' => 'Chatuchak Weekend Market', 'description' => 'Chatuchak Weekend Market is one of the world\'s largest and most diverse weekend markets, covering 27 acres (11 hectares) with over 15,000 stalls. The market attracts over 200,000 visitors every weekend. It\'s divided into 27 sections selling everything imaginable: clothing, accessories, handicrafts, antiques, furniture, ceramics, art, books, plants, pets, food, and drinks. The market is a maze of narrow alleys, and it\'s easy to get lost. Bargaining is expected. The market is particularly famous for its street food, offering authentic Thai dishes at cheap prices. It\'s best visited early morning to avoid the heat and crowds. The market is open Saturdays and Sundays from 9 AM to 6 PM.', 'localisation' => '13.8000, 100.5500', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1552465011-b4e21bf6e79a?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Chiang Mai (id: 8)
            ['city_id' => 8, 'name' => 'Doi Suthep', 'description' => 'Wat Phra That Doi Suthep is a sacred Buddhist temple perched on Doi Suthep mountain, overlooking the city of Chiang Mai. The temple was founded in 1383 and is one of northern Thailand\'s most important religious sites. Legend says that a white elephant carrying a relic of the Buddha climbed Doi Suthep, trumpeted three times, and died, which was interpreted as a sign to build the temple. Visitors climb 306 steps (or take a funicular) to reach the temple, where they encounter a golden chedi (stupa), beautifully decorated shrines, and panoramic views of Chiang Mai. The temple is particularly beautiful at sunset. The surrounding national park offers hiking trails and waterfalls.', 'localisation' => '18.8048, 98.9218', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1528181304807-1f2e7c1425b7?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 8, 'name' => 'Old City Temples', 'description' => 'Chiang Mai\'s Old City is a square-walled area that contains over 30 ancient temples, reflecting the city\'s history as the capital of the Lanna Kingdom. The most significant temples include Wat Phra Singh (housing the Phra Buddha Sihing, a highly revered Buddha image), Wat Chedi Luang (once housing the Emerald Buddha, with a massive ruined chedi), Wat Chiang Man (the oldest temple in Chiang Mai), and Wat Phan Tao (with a beautiful teakwood viharn). The Old City is surrounded by a moat and remnants of the original walls. Exploring the temples on foot is the best way to appreciate their beauty, especially early in the morning when monks are chanting.', 'localisation' => '18.7904, 98.9851', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1528181304807-1f2e7c1425b7?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 8, 'name' => 'Elephant Nature Park', 'description' => 'Elephant Nature Park is an ethical elephant sanctuary and rescue center located about 60 kilometers from Chiang Mai. Unlike many elephant camps that offer riding or shows, this park allows elephants to roam freely and behave naturally. The park rescues elephants that have been abused, injured, or abandoned, providing them with medical care and a safe home. Visitors can observe elephants bathing in the river, feed them, and walk with them, learning about elephant behavior and conservation from knowledgeable guides. The park also rescues dogs, cats, buffaloes, and other animals. A visit is educational and emotional, offering a deeper understanding of Thailand\'s elephant tourism issues.', 'localisation' => '19.2000, 98.8500', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1528181304807-1f2e7c1425b7?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Phuket (id: 9)
            ['city_id' => 9, 'name' => 'Phi Phi Islands', 'description' => 'The Phi Phi Islands are an archipelago of six islands in the Andaman Sea, known for their stunning limestone cliffs, crystal-clear turquoise water, and beautiful beaches. The islands gained worldwide fame as the filming location for the movie "The Beach" (starring Leonardo DiCaprio), which was filmed on Maya Bay on Phi Phi Leh. The main islands are Phi Phi Don (the only inhabited island) and Phi Phi Leh (uninhabited). Popular activities include snorkeling, diving, rock climbing, and boat tours. The Viking Cave features ancient paintings. The islands are particularly beautiful at sunrise and sunset. Day trips from Phuket or Krabi are popular, but overnight stays allow you to experience the islands without crowds.', 'localisation' => '7.7400, 98.7700', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1552465011-b4e21bf6e79a?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 9, 'name' => 'Big Buddha Phuket', 'description' => 'The Big Buddha (Phra Phuttha Ming Mongkol Akenakiri) is a massive white marble Buddha statue perched on top of Nakkerd Hill between Chalong and Kata. The statue stands 45 meters tall and 25 meters wide, making it one of Phuket\'s most important and visible landmarks. Construction began in 2004 and continues, funded by donations. The Buddha is made of Burmese white marble, which sparkles in the sun. The site offers 360-degree panoramic views of Phuket, including Chalong Bay, Kata, Karon, and the Andaman Sea. The statue faces north toward Bangkok. The site is also home to a smaller golden Buddha, bells, and a meditation center. The best time to visit is sunrise or sunset for the views and cooler temperatures.', 'localisation' => '7.8275, 98.3320', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1552465011-b4e21bf6e79a?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 9, 'name' => 'Old Phuket Town', 'description' => 'Old Phuket Town is the historic heart of Phuket, known for its beautifully preserved Sino-Portuguese architecture dating from the tin mining boom of the late 19th and early 20th centuries. The streets, particularly Soi Romanee, Thalang Road, and Dibuk Road, are lined with colorful shop-houses with ornate facades, shuttered windows, and interior courtyards. The architecture reflects the influence of Chinese and European traders. The area has become a hub for boutique hotels, cafes, art galleries, and restaurants. The Phuket Thai Hua Museum (formerly a Chinese language school) and the Phuket Peranakan Museum showcase the local heritage. The area comes alive on Sundays for the Lard Yai Sunday Walking Street Market.', 'localisation' => '7.8830, 98.3850', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1552465011-b4e21bf6e79a?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // ==================== FRANCE (City IDs 10-12) ====================
            // Paris (id: 10)
            ['city_id' => 10, 'name' => 'Eiffel Tower', 'description' => 'The Eiffel Tower is the most iconic landmark in Paris and one of the most recognizable structures in the world. Built by Gustave Eiffel for the 1889 World\'s Fair, the tower was initially criticized by artists and intellectuals but has become a beloved symbol of France. Standing 330 meters tall (including antennas), it was the world\'s tallest structure until 1930. The tower has three observation levels: the first floor with glass floors, the second floor with the best views for photos, and the top floor with panoramic views up to 70 kilometers on clear days. The tower sparkles with 20,000 light bulbs for five minutes every hour after sunset. Over 250 million people have visited the tower, making it the most visited paid monument in the world.', 'localisation' => '48.8584, 2.2945', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1502602898657-3e91760cbb34?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 10, 'name' => 'Louvre Museum', 'description' => 'The Louvre is the world\'s largest art museum and a historic monument in Paris, housed in the former royal palace. It holds over 380,000 objects and displays 35,000 works of art across eight curatorial departments. The museum\'s most famous piece is Leonardo da Vinci\'s Mona Lisa, but other masterpieces include the Venus de Milo, Winged Victory of Samothrace, Liberty Leading the People by Delacroix, and The Raft of the Medusa by Géricault. The Louvre Pyramid, designed by I.M. Pei and completed in 1989, serves as the main entrance. The museum is so vast that it would take 100 days to see every piece if you spent 30 seconds on each. The Louvre is a must-visit for art lovers and history enthusiasts.', 'localisation' => '48.8606, 2.3376', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1566643226668-7c2f540a42e3?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 10, 'name' => 'Notre-Dame Cathedral', 'description' => 'Notre-Dame de Paris is a medieval Catholic cathedral and one of the finest examples of French Gothic architecture. Construction began in 1163 and was completed in 1345. The cathedral is famous for its flying buttresses, massive rose windows, and the iconic gargoyles and chimeras. The towers offer spectacular views of Paris and house the famous Emmanuel bell. The cathedral was severely damaged by a fire on April 15, 2019, which destroyed the spire and roof. Restoration work is underway, with plans to reopen in December 2024. Despite the fire, the cathedral remains a powerful symbol of French culture and history. Visitors can still view the cathedral from outside and visit the archaeological crypt.', 'localisation' => '48.8530, 2.3499', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1502602898657-3e91760cbb34?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // French Riviera (id: 11)
            ['city_id' => 11, 'name' => 'Promenade des Anglais', 'description' => 'The Promenade des Anglais is the famous seaside walkway in Nice, stretching for 7 kilometers along the Mediterranean coast. The promenade was built in the 19th century by English aristocrats who wintered in Nice, hence the name "Walkway of the English." It features a wide pedestrian path, a bike lane, and iconic blue "chaises bleues" (blue chairs). The promenade is lined with palm trees, luxury hotels (including the Negresco), restaurants, and art deco buildings. It\'s a popular spot for walking, jogging, cycling, and rollerblading. The Baie des Anges (Bay of Angels) offers beautiful views, especially at sunset. The Nice Carnival and other events take place along the promenade. It\'s the heart of Nice\'s seaside life.', 'localisation' => '43.6950, 7.2600', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1505852903341-fc8d3db1047d?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 11, 'name' => 'Monte Carlo Casino', 'description' => 'The Monte Carlo Casino is one of the world\'s most famous casinos, located in the sovereign city-state of Monaco. Designed by Charles Garnier (who also designed the Paris Opera), the casino opened in 1863 and helped establish Monaco as a destination for the wealthy. The Belle Époque building features a stunning facade, marble atrium, and ornate gaming rooms, including the Salle Médecin (main gaming room) and the Salle Blanche (now used for poker). The casino also houses the Opera de Monte-Carlo (Salle Garnier). The casino has appeared in numerous James Bond films, including "GoldenEye" and "Casino Royale." Visitors need passports to enter, and formal dress is required for the main gaming rooms. Even non-gamblers can admire the architecture.', 'localisation' => '43.7393, 7.4273', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1505852903341-fc8d3db1047d?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 11, 'name' => 'Saint-Tropez', 'description' => 'Saint-Tropez is a glamorous port town on the French Riviera, known for its beautiful harbor, celebrity residents, and vibrant nightlife. The town was a quiet fishing village until the 1950s when it gained fame as the filming location for "And God Created Woman" starring Brigitte Bardot, who made the town her home. Today, the old port (Vieux Port) is filled with luxury yachts. The town\'s attractions include the Citadel (a 17th-century fortress with panoramic views and a maritime museum), the Place des Lices (a square with a Provençal market), and the Annonciade Museum (with a collection of modern art). The surrounding beaches, including Pampelonne Beach, are lined with private beach clubs. Saint-Tropez represents the glamorous side of the Riviera.', 'localisation' => '43.2700, 6.6400', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1505852903341-fc8d3db1047d?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Bordeaux (id: 12)
            ['city_id' => 12, 'name' => 'Place de la Bourse', 'description' => 'Place de la Bourse is one of Bordeaux\'s most iconic squares, designed by architect Ange-Jacques Gabriel between 1730 and 1775. The square features two magnificent 18th-century buildings: the Hôtel des Fermes (now the Chamber of Commerce) and the Hôtel de la Bourse (now the National Interprofessional Office for Cognac). In front of the square is the Miroir d\'Eau (Water Mirror), the world\'s largest reflecting pool (3,450 square meters). The water mirror alternates between a mirror effect, mist, and shallow water, creating beautiful reflections of the buildings. At night, the square and the water mirror are illuminated. The square faces the Garonne River and offers beautiful views. It\'s a UNESCO World Heritage site and the most photographed spot in Bordeaux.', 'localisation' => '44.8417, -0.5699', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1513026705753-bc3dca4d74b8?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 12, 'name' => 'Cité du Vin', 'description' => 'The Cité du Vin is a stunning modern wine museum and cultural center in Bordeaux, designed by architects Anouk Legendre and Nicolas Desmazières (XTU Architects). The building\'s curvilinear shape symbolizes the swirl of wine in a glass and the flow of the Garonne River. The museum offers an immersive journey through the history, culture, and civilizations of wine from around the world, with interactive exhibits, multi-sensory experiences, and a "Buffet of World Wines" on the 8th floor with panoramic views. The permanent exhibition covers wine in art, religion, literature, and science. The Belvedere offers 360-degree views of Bordeaux. The museum also hosts temporary exhibitions, workshops, tastings, and a restaurant. It\'s a must-visit for wine lovers.', 'localisation' => '44.8606, -0.5520', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1513026705753-bc3dca4d74b8?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 12, 'name' => 'Saint-Émilion', 'description' => 'Saint-Émilion is a picturesque medieval village in the Bordeaux wine region, a UNESCO World Heritage site. The village is famous for its wine, with over 1,200 vineyards in the surrounding area producing some of the world\'s most prestigious wines (including Cheval Blanc, Ausone, and Angélus). The village itself is built on a limestone hill and features narrow, winding streets, stone houses, and historic monuments, including the Monolithic Church (the largest underground church in Europe, carved from a single block of limestone), the King\'s Tower (offering panoramic views), and the Collégiale (collegiate church). Visitors can explore wine cellars (including underground cellars carved into the limestone), attend wine tastings, and hike through the vineyards. The village is especially beautiful in autumn during the harvest season.', 'localisation' => '44.8933, -0.1561', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1513026705753-bc3dca4d74b8?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // ==================== AUSTRALIA (City IDs 13-15) ====================
            // Sydney (id: 13)
            ['city_id' => 13, 'name' => 'Sydney Opera House', 'description' => 'The Sydney Opera House is one of the 20th century\'s most famous and distinctive buildings, a UNESCO World Heritage site, and Australia\'s most recognizable landmark. Designed by Danish architect Jørn Utzon, the building features a series of large shell-like structures that resemble sails or waves. The Opera House opened in 1973 and hosts over 1,500 performances annually, including opera, theater, dance, concerts, and comedy. The complex includes multiple venues: the Concert Hall (with the world\'s largest mechanical pipe organ), the Joan Sutherland Theatre, the Drama Theatre, and the Playhouse. Visitors can take guided tours, attend performances, or dine at the waterfront restaurants. The building is spectacularly illuminated for special events, including Vivid Sydney, a festival of light, music, and ideas.', 'localisation' => '-33.8568, 151.2153', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1506973035872-a4ec16b8e8d9?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 13, 'name' => 'Sydney Harbour Bridge', 'description' => 'The Sydney Harbour Bridge, nicknamed "The Coathanger" because of its arch design, is the world\'s tallest steel arch bridge and a symbol of Sydney. Completed in 1932, the bridge connects the Sydney central business district with the North Shore. The BridgeClimb experience allows visitors to climb to the top of the arch (134 meters above the harbor) for breathtaking 360-degree views. For a less adventurous experience, visitors can walk or cycle across the bridge, or take the Pylon Lookout at the southeastern pylon for excellent views at a lower cost. The bridge is spectacularly illuminated at night and features the world\'s largest fireworks display on New Year\'s Eve. The bridge is also a popular spot for sunrise photography.', 'localisation' => '-33.8523, 151.2108', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1506973035872-a4ec16b8e8d9?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 13, 'name' => 'Bondi Beach', 'description' => 'Bondi Beach is one of Australia\'s most famous beaches, located just 7 kilometers from Sydney\'s city center. The golden sand beach stretches about one kilometer and is popular for surfing, swimming, and sunbathing. The beach is patrolled by lifeguards year-round and has strong rips, so swimming between the flags is essential. The Bondi to Coogee coastal walk offers stunning ocean views and passes through several other beaches, parks, and cemeteries. Bondi is also known for its vibrant café culture, with numerous restaurants, bars, and boutiques along Campbell Parade and Gould Street. The weekend Bondi Markets offer fashion, art, and crafts. The annual Sculpture by the Sea exhibition features sculptures along the coastal walk. Bondi embodies Sydney\'s beach lifestyle.', 'localisation' => '-33.8915, 151.2767', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1506973035872-a4ec16b8e8d9?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Great Barrier Reef (id: 14)
            ['city_id' => 14, 'name' => 'Heart Reef', 'description' => 'Heart Reef is a naturally formed heart-shaped coral reef located in the Whitsunday Islands region of the Great Barrier Reef. Discovered in 1975 by an aerial survey pilot, Heart Reef has become one of the Great Barrier Reef\'s most iconic symbols and a popular spot for romantic proposals. The reef is located in Hardy Reef, about 70 kilometers from Airlie Beach. Due to its protected status, boats are not permitted to access Heart Reef directly, but visitors can view it from scenic flights (helicopter or seaplane) departing from Airlie Beach, Hamilton Island, or other Whitsunday launch points. The heart shape is about 17 meters wide at its widest point. The best time for viewing is at low tide when the coral is most visible.', 'localisation' => '-20.0000, 148.5000', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1582967788606-a171c1080cb0?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 14, 'name' => 'Whitehaven Beach', 'description' => 'Whitehaven Beach is a stunning 7-kilometer stretch of white silica sand on Whitsunday Island, the largest of the Whitsunday Islands. The sand is 98% pure silica, which gives it a brilliant white color and does not retain heat, making it comfortable to walk on even in hot weather. The beach has been voted one of the world\'s top beaches numerous times. The Hill Inlet, at the northern end of the beach, offers a spectacular view where the tide shifts the sand and water to create beautiful swirling patterns. Visitors can reach Whitehaven Beach by boat, kayak, or scenic flight from Airlie Beach, Hamilton Island, or other Whitsunday launch points. Swimming, sunbathing, and walking are popular activities. No accommodation is available on the island, so visits are day trips only.', 'localisation' => '-20.2780, 149.0380', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1582967788606-a171c1080cb0?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 14, 'name' => 'Whitsunday Islands', 'description' => 'The Whitsunday Islands are an archipelago of 74 tropical islands off the coast of Queensland, Australia, located in the heart of the Great Barrier Reef. The islands are a popular destination for sailing, yachting, camping, and hiking. Only a few islands are developed with resorts, including Hamilton Island (the most developed, with an airport, hotels, and restaurants), Daydream Island, and Hayman Island (luxury resort). Hook Island offers excellent snorkeling and hiking. Whitsunday Island is uninhabited and home to Whitehaven Beach. The islands offer stunning scenery, with turquoise water, white sand beaches, and lush rainforest. The best way to experience the islands is by sailing tour, which can include snorkeling at reef sites, beach visits, and overnight stays on boats or islands.', 'localisation' => '-20.3000, 148.9000', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1582967788606-a171c1080cb0?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Melbourne (id: 15)
            ['city_id' => 15, 'name' => 'Great Ocean Road', 'description' => 'The Great Ocean Road is a 243-kilometer scenic coastal drive in Victoria, Australia, known as one of the world\'s most spectacular road trips. Built by returned soldiers between 1919 and 1932 as a memorial to those killed in World War I, it is the world\'s largest war memorial. The road winds along the rugged coastline, passing through rainforests, beaches, and cliffs. The most famous section is the Port Campbell National Park, home to the Twelve Apostles (limestone stacks rising from the ocean), Loch Ard Gorge, London Arch, and the Grotto. Other highlights include the surf town of Torquay (home of Rip Curl and Quiksilver), the Cape Otway Lighthouse, and the Great Otway National Park. The drive can be done in one day but is best enjoyed over two to three days.', 'localisation' => '-38.6500, 143.8500', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1514395462725-fb4566210144?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 15, 'name' => 'Federation Square', 'description' => 'Federation Square (Fed Square) is Melbourne\'s central public square and cultural precinct, located in the heart of the city opposite Flinders Street Station. Completed in 2002, the square features a striking design of deconstructivist architecture, with a facade of twisted and angled buildings clad in sandstone, zinc, and glass. The square houses cultural institutions including the Ian Potter Centre (part of the National Gallery of Victoria, dedicated to Australian art), the Australian Centre for the Moving Image (ACMI), and the Koorie Heritage Trust (dedicated to Aboriginal culture). The square hosts free events, concerts, festivals, and sports broadcasts on the big screen. The plaza is paved with 470,000 sandstone blocks. It\'s a popular meeting place and a symbol of modern Melbourne.', 'localisation' => '-37.8175, 144.9690', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1514395462725-fb4566210144?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 15, 'name' => 'Royal Botanic Gardens', 'description' => 'The Royal Botanic Gardens Victoria (RBGV) in Melbourne covers 38 hectares in the heart of the city, near the Yarra River. Founded in 1846, the gardens are one of the world\'s finest examples of botanic gardens, with over 8,500 plant species from around the world. Highlights include the Guilfoyle\'s Volcano (a historic water reservoir), the Children\'s Garden, the Fern Gully, the Arid Garden (with cacti and succulents), and the Ornamental Lake (home to eels and birds). The gardens also feature the Ian Potter Foundation Children\'s Garden, the National Herbarium of Victoria, and the Observatory. Free guided walks are offered daily. The gardens are particularly beautiful in spring when the flowers are in bloom, and in autumn when the leaves change color. They\'re a peaceful escape from the city.', 'localisation' => '-37.8300, 144.9800', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1514395462725-fb4566210144?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // ==================== BRAZIL (City IDs 16-18) ====================
            // Rio de Janeiro (id: 16)
            ['city_id' => 16, 'name' => 'Christ the Redeemer', 'description' => 'Christ the Redeemer is an iconic Art Deco statue of Jesus Christ located atop Corcovado Mountain in Rio de Janeiro. The statue stands 30 meters tall (38 meters including pedestal) with arms stretching 28 meters wide, making it the largest Art Deco sculpture in the world. Completed in 1931, the statue has become a symbol of Brazilian Christianity and one of the New Seven Wonders of the World. Visitors reach the statue via a cog train through Tijuca Forest, followed by escalators and elevators. The views from the base are spectacular, overlooking Rio\'s mountains, beaches, and the lagoon. The statue is particularly impressive at sunset when the sky changes colors and the statue is illuminated. Christ the Redeemer is Rio\'s most famous landmark and a must-visit for any traveler.', 'localisation' => '-22.9519, -43.2105', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1483729558449-99ef09a8c325?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 16, 'name' => 'Sugarloaf Mountain', 'description' => 'Sugarloaf Mountain (Pão de Açúcar) is a 396-meter peak at the mouth of Guanabara Bay, offering spectacular 360-degree views of Rio de Janeiro. Visitors reach the summit via a two-stage cable car system: first to Morro da Urca (224 meters), then to Sugarloaf itself. The cable car ride offers stunning views of Copacabana, Botafogo, and the city. The summit has observation decks, a bar, a restaurant, and a souvenir shop. The sunset is the most popular time to visit, when the city is bathed in golden light. The mountain gets its name from its resemblance to traditional sugarloaf molds. The area is also a popular rock climbing destination, with over 270 climbing routes. Sugarloaf Mountain offers the best panoramic views of Rio.', 'localisation' => '-22.9491, -43.1536', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1483729558449-99ef09a8c325?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 16, 'name' => 'Copacabana Beach', 'description' => 'Copacabana Beach is one of the most famous beaches in the world, stretching 4 kilometers along Rio\'s Atlantic coast. The beach is divided into sections by lifeguard posts (postos), each with its own character. Posto 2 is the most popular for swimming, Posto 5 is popular with families, and Posto 6 (Leme) is quieter. The beach is famous for its black and white wave-patterned promenade (calçadão), a symbol of Rio. Copacabana hosts the world\'s largest New Year\'s Eve celebration (Réveillon) with 2 million people watching fireworks. The beach is surrounded by hotels, restaurants, bars, and shops. The iconic Copacabana Palace Hotel has hosted celebrities and royalty since 1923. Copacabana embodies the carioca lifestyle and the spirit of Rio.', 'localisation' => '-22.9671, -43.1807', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1483729558449-99ef09a8c325?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Amazon Rainforest (id: 17)
            ['city_id' => 17, 'name' => 'Meeting of Waters', 'description' => 'The Meeting of Waters (Encontro das Águas) is a natural phenomenon near Manaus, where the dark Rio Negro and the sandy-colored Amazon River (Rio Solimões) flow side by side for 6 kilometers without mixing. The rivers have different temperatures, speeds, and densities: the Rio Negro is darker (from decaying plant matter), slower, and warmer (22°C), while the Solimões is lighter, faster, and cooler (28°C). The phenomenon occurs for about 6 kilometers before the rivers eventually mix. Visitors can view the Meeting of Waters from boat tours departing from Manaus. The tours often include visits to floating villages, swimming with pink river dolphins, and exploring the Amazon jungle. The best time to see the phenomenon is during the dry season (July to December) when the contrast is most visible.', 'localisation' => '-3.1330, -60.0000', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516026672322-bc52d61a55d5?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 17, 'name' => 'Amazon River', 'description' => 'The Amazon River is the world\'s largest river by volume (accounting for about 20% of the world\'s freshwater discharge into the oceans) and the second-longest (after the Nile). It flows approximately 6,400 kilometers from the Andes in Peru through Brazil to the Atlantic Ocean. The river is home to thousands of species, including pink river dolphins, piranhas, anacondas, caimans, and the giant arapaima fish. The Amazon Basin is the world\'s largest rainforest. Visitors can explore the Amazon River from gateway cities like Manaus (Brazil), Iquitos (Peru), and Leticia (Colombia). Activities include boat tours, fishing for piranhas, night safaris to spot caimans, visiting indigenous communities, and exploring flooded forests (várzea). The river is at its highest during the rainy season (March to May).', 'localisation' => '-3.0000, -60.0000', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516026672322-bc52d61a55d5?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 17, 'name' => 'Anavilhanas Archipelago', 'description' => 'The Anavilhanas Archipelago is the world\'s largest freshwater archipelago, located in the Rio Negro about 90 kilometers upstream from Manaus. The archipelago consists of over 400 islands, flooded forests (igapó), channels, and lakes, covering 3,500 square kilometers. It is part of the Rio Negro Sustainable Development Reserve. During the wet season (March to May), the water level rises up to 15 meters, flooding the islands and creating a labyrinth of channels. During the dry season (July to December), beaches and trails appear. The archipelago is home to diverse wildlife, including monkeys, sloths, caimans, pink river dolphins, and hundreds of bird species. Visitors can explore by boat, kayak, or canoe, with tours departing from Manaus or the village of Novo Airão. Camping and jungle lodges are available on some islands.', 'localisation' => '-2.0000, -61.0000', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516026672322-bc52d61a55d5?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Salvador (id: 18)
            ['city_id' => 18, 'name' => 'Pelourinho', 'description' => 'Pelourinho is the historic center of Salvador, a UNESCO World Heritage site known for its colorful colonial buildings, cobblestone streets, and Afro-Brazilian culture. The name "Pelourinho" means "pillory" in Portuguese, referring to the whipping post where enslaved people were publicly punished during the colonial era. Today, the area is a vibrant cultural hub, with restored 17th and 18th-century buildings in bright pastel colors. Highlights include the São Francisco Church (with its gold-leaf interior), the Cathedral of Salvador, the Largo do Pelourinho (main square), and the Jorge Amado Museum (dedicated to Brazil\'s most famous writer). The area is famous for capoeira performances, live music, and traditional Bahian cuisine. Pelourinho comes alive at night with bars, restaurants, and street parties.', 'localisation' => '-12.9700, -38.5100', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516307365426-bea591f05011?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 18, 'name' => 'São Francisco Church', 'description' => 'The Church of São Francisco (Igreja de São Francisco) is one of Brazil\'s most spectacular Baroque churches, located in Pelourinho, Salvador. The church was built between 1686 and 1723 by Franciscan monks. The interior is covered in gold leaf, earning it the nickname "Golden Church." It\'s estimated that the church contains over 100 kilograms of gold. The gold-covered woodcarvings, paintings, and sculptures create an overwhelming visual experience. The church also features beautiful Portuguese tiles (azulejos) depicting scenes from the life of Saint Francis. The adjoining Convent of São Francisco includes the Cloister (with blue and white azulejos), the Chapel of the Third Order, and the Museum of Sacred Art. The church is a masterpiece of Brazilian colonial architecture and a must-see for art and history lovers.', 'localisation' => '-12.9700, -38.5100', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516307365426-bea591f05011?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 18, 'name' => 'Elevador Lacerda', 'description' => 'The Elevador Lacerda (Lacerda Elevator) is a public elevator connecting Salvador\'s lower city (Cidade Baixa) with the upper city (Cidade Alta). The elevator was first opened in 1873 and was the first urban elevator in the world. The current structure, designed by the Lacerda engineering firm, was completed in 1930. The elevator stands 72 meters tall and has four cabins, each carrying 20 passengers (or 27 after renovation). The ride takes about 15 seconds. The elevator offers spectacular views of Todos os Santos Bay (Baía de Todos os Santos). The upper station is located in the historic center near Pelourinho, while the lower station is at the Mercado Modelo (craft market) and the port. The elevator transports over 900,000 people per month. It\'s a quick and cheap way to travel between the two levels of the city.', 'localisation' => '-12.9740, -38.5120', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516307365426-bea591f05011?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
         // Jaipur (id: 19)
            ['city_id' => 19, 'name' => 'Hawa Mahal', 'description' => 'Hawa Mahal, or "Palace of Winds," is a stunning five-story palace in Jaipur built in 1799 by Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh. The palace features a unique honeycomb design with 953 small windows (jharokhas) decorated with intricate lattice work. The palace was designed for royal women to observe street festivals and daily life without being seen, as they were required to observe purdah (veil). The lattice work allows cool air to circulate, keeping the palace naturally air-conditioned (hence the name). The palace is made of red and pink sandstone, matching Jaipur\'s Pink City aesthetic. The top floors offer beautiful views of the City Palace and Jantar Mantar. There are no stairs; instead, ramps lead to the upper floors. Hawa Mahal is one of Jaipur\'s most iconic landmarks, especially beautiful when illuminated at night.', 'localisation' => '26.9239, 75.8267', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1537996194471-e657df975ab4?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 19, 'name' => 'Amber Fort', 'description' => 'Amber Fort (Amer Fort) is a magnificent hill fort located in Amer, about 11 kilometers from Jaipur. The fort was built in the 16th century by Raja Man Singh I and served as the capital of the Kachwaha Rajputs before Jaipur. The fort is a stunning blend of Hindu and Mughal architecture, built with red sandstone and white marble. Highlights include the Sheesh Mahal (Mirror Palace), covered with thousands of mirror tiles; the Diwan-e-Aam (Hall of Public Audience); the Diwan-e-Khas (Hall of Private Audience); the Sukh Niwas (Hall of Pleasure) with a cooling water system; and the Ganesh Pol (Ganesh Gate). Visitors can reach the fort by walking, taking a jeep, or riding an elephant. The fort offers spectacular views of Maota Lake below and the surrounding hills. It\'s a UNESCO World Heritage site (part of the Hill Forts of Rajasthan).', 'localisation' => '26.9856, 75.8508', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1537996194471-e657df975ab4?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 19, 'name' => 'City Palace', 'description' => 'The City Palace is a magnificent palace complex in the heart of Jaipur, built between 1729 and 1732 by Maharaja Sawai Jai Singh II, the founder of Jaipur. The palace served as the seat of the Maharaja of Jaipur and is still the residence of the current royal family. The complex features a blend of Rajput, Mughal, and European architecture, with courtyards, gardens, museums, and temples. Highlights include the Mubarak Mahal (Welcome Palace, now a museum of royal costumes and textiles), the Diwan-e-Khas (Hall of Private Audience, with two massive silver vessels), the Diwan-e-Aam (Hall of Public Audience), the Pritam Niwas Chowk (a courtyard with four beautiful gates representing the four seasons), and the Chandra Mahal (the royal residence, not open to the public). The palace also houses a museum with rare manuscripts, weapons, carpets, and paintings.', 'localisation' => '26.9257, 75.8236', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1537996194471-e657df975ab4?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Goa (id: 20)
            ['city_id' => 20, 'name' => 'Baga Beach', 'description' => 'Baga Beach is one of North Goa\'s most popular beaches, known for its vibrant nightlife, water sports, and beach shacks. The beach is located in Baga village, adjacent to Calangute Beach. The main attraction is the Baga Creek at the northern end, where the Baga River meets the Arabian Sea. The beach is famous for water sports including parasailing, jet skiing, banana boat rides, and bumper rides. The beach is lined with beach shacks serving seafood, drinks, and Goan cuisine. At night, the area comes alive with nightclubs (including Tito\'s, Mambo\'s, and Club Cubana), bars, and discos. The Saturday Night Market near Arpora offers shopping, food, and entertainment. Baga is also known for its New Year\'s Eve celebrations. While popular with party-goers, the beach can be crowded and loud, especially during peak season (November to February).', 'localisation' => '15.5600, 73.7400', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1512343879784-a960bf40e7f2?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 20, 'name' => 'Basilica of Bom Jesus', 'description' => 'The Basilica of Bom Jesus is a UNESCO World Heritage site and one of Goa\'s most important churches, located in Old Goa. The basilica was built in 1594 and consecrated in 1605. It holds the mortal remains of St. Francis Xavier, a Spanish Jesuit missionary who died in 1552. His body is preserved in a silver casket in the church\'s mausoleum. The church is considered one of the best examples of Baroque architecture in India, with a simple exterior but elaborate interior. The main altar features a statue of St. Francis Xavier. The church is named "Bom Jesus" (Good Jesus) and is the only church in Old Goa not plastered on the outside. The body of St. Francis Xavier is exposed for public veneration every ten years (last in 2014). The basilica attracts pilgrims and tourists from around the world.', 'localisation' => '15.5000, 73.9100', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1512343879784-a960bf40e7f2?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 20, 'name' => 'Dudhsagar Falls', 'description' => 'Dudhsagar Falls is one of India\'s tallest waterfalls, located on the Mandovi River in the Bhagwan Mahaveer Sanctuary and Mollem National Park, on the border between Goa and Karnataka. The name "Dudhsagar" means "Sea of Milk" in Hindi, referring to the milky white appearance of the water as it cascades down. The falls are 310 meters tall (one of India\'s highest) and have four tiers. The best time to visit is during and just after the monsoon season (October to February), when the water flow is strongest. Visitors can reach the falls by trekking through the jungle (about 10 kilometers), by jeep safari, or by train (the Dudhsagar railway station is near the falls). Swimming is possible at the base of the falls but can be dangerous during high water. The falls are surrounded by lush jungle and are home to wildlife including monkeys, birds, and butterflies.', 'localisation' => '15.3200, 74.3100', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1512343879784-a960bf40e7f2?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Manali (id: 21)
            ['city_id' => 21, 'name' => 'Rohtang Pass', 'description' => 'Rohtang Pass is a high mountain pass on the Pir Panjal range of the Himalayas, located about 51 kilometers from Manali at an altitude of 3,978 meters (13,050 feet). The pass connects the Kullu Valley with the Lahaul and Spiti Valleys. The name "Rohtang" means "pile of corpses" in Tibetan, referring to the many people who died trying to cross the pass. The pass is famous for its stunning views of the surrounding peaks, glaciers, and valleys. It is a popular destination for snow activities, including skiing, snowboarding, snowmobiling, and sledding, especially from April to June when the pass is accessible but still has snow. The pass is only open from May to November (weather permitting) and requires a permit for vehicles. Visitors can experience altitude sickness symptoms due to the high elevation. The pass offers breathtaking views of the Chandra River and the Lahaul Valley.', 'localisation' => '32.3700, 77.2500', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1501786223405-6d024d7c3b8d?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 21, 'name' => 'Hadimba Temple', 'description' => 'Hadimba Temple is a unique ancient cave temple dedicated to Hadimba, the wife of Bhima (one of the Pandava brothers from the Hindu epic Mahabharata). The temple is located in Manali, surrounded by a cedar forest (dhungri forest). The temple was built in 1553 and features a four-tiered pagoda-style roof and a wooden door carved with deities. The temple walls are made of stone and wood, and the floor is covered with animal skins. The temple has a distinctive structure, with a wooden conical roof and a metal image of Hadimba inside. The temple is also known as Dhungri Temple. The surrounding forest is home to many monkeys. The temple hosts the Hadimba Devi fair every May. The setting is peaceful and atmospheric, especially in the morning when the forest is misty. It\'s one of Manali\'s most visited attractions.', 'localisation' => '32.2500, 77.1800', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1501786223405-6d024d7c3b8d?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 21, 'name' => 'Solang Valley', 'description' => 'Solang Valley is a beautiful valley located about 14 kilometers from Manali, at an altitude of 2,560 meters (8,400 feet). The valley is famous for adventure sports and stunning views of the surrounding snow-capped peaks, including Mount Hanuman Tibba. In winter (December to February), the valley becomes a ski resort, with skiing, snowboarding, snowmobiling, and paragliding. The valley also has a ropeway (cable car) offering panoramic views. In summer (May to October), the valley offers activities like zorbing (rolling down hills in a giant ball), quad biking, horse riding, rock climbing, and mountain biking. The Solang River flows through the valley, adding to its beauty. The valley is particularly beautiful in spring when wildflowers bloom. It\'s a popular day trip from Manali for adventure enthusiasts and families. The valley also has small cafes and food stalls.', 'localisation' => '32.3100, 77.1600', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1501786223405-6d024d7c3b8d?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // ==================== CANADA (City IDs 22-24) ====================
            // Banff (id: 22)
            ['city_id' => 22, 'name' => 'Lake Louise', 'description' => 'Lake Louise is a stunning glacial lake in Banff National Park, known for its turquoise blue water and the Victoria Glacier behind it. The lake is named after Princess Louise Caroline Alberta, daughter of Queen Victoria. The vibrant color comes from rock flour (fine rock particles) carried by the meltwater from the glacier. The lake is surrounded by the peaks of the Canadian Rockies, including Mount Victoria, Mount Whyte, and Mount Niblock. The Fairmont Chateau Lake Louise, a luxury hotel, sits on the lake\'s shore. Activities include canoeing on the lake (summer), hiking to the Lake Agnes Teahouse, Plain of Six Glaciers, or Big Beehive, and cross-country skiing (winter). The lake is most beautiful in summer when it\'s ice-free and in winter when it freezes over and becomes a skating rink. It\'s one of Canada\'s most photographed locations.', 'localisation' => '51.4100, -116.2300', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1503614472-8c93d56e92ce?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 22, 'name' => 'Moraine Lake', 'description' => 'Moraine Lake is a stunning glacial lake in Banff National Park, located in the Valley of the Ten Peaks. The lake is known for its vivid turquoise color, created by light refracting off the rock flour deposited in the lake by glacier meltwater. The lake is surrounded by ten peaks, giving it the name Valley of the Ten Peaks. The view of the lake from the Rockpile (a natural rock formation) is one of the most famous and photographed scenes in the Canadian Rockies, once featured on the back of the Canadian $20 bill. The lake is only accessible from late May to mid-October due to snow. Activities include canoeing (canoes are available for rent), hiking to Sentinel Pass, Eiffel Lake, or Consolation Lakes, and photography. The Moraine Lake Lodge offers accommodations on the lake\'s shore. The lake is at its most beautiful in late June and July when the water level is highest.', 'localisation' => '51.3200, -116.1800', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1503614472-8c93d56e92ce?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 22, 'name' => 'Banff Gondola', 'description' => 'The Banff Gondola is a cable car that takes visitors to the summit of Sulphur Mountain (2,281 meters) for spectacular panoramic views of Banff, the Bow Valley, and the surrounding Canadian Rockies. The 8-minute ride offers stunning views of six mountain ranges. At the summit, visitors can explore the boardwalk to the Sanson Peak Meteorological Station (built in 1903), visit the Above Banff Interpretive Centre (with exhibits on the area\'s history and wildlife), dine at the Sky Bistro (with floor-to-ceiling windows), or enjoy the Northern Lights Alpine Kitchen (a cafeteria). The summit also has a gift shop and a rooftop observation deck. The gondola operates year-round, but winter offers views of snow-covered peaks and the chance to see the northern lights. Sunset is the most popular time, offering beautiful golden light and the chance to see the town lights below.', 'localisation' => '51.1600, -115.5600', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1503614472-8c93d56e92ce?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Vancouver (id: 23)
            ['city_id' => 23, 'name' => 'Stanley Park', 'description' => 'Stanley Park is Vancouver\'s largest and most famous urban park, covering 405 hectares (1,001 acres) at the northwestern edge of downtown Vancouver. The park is surrounded by the waters of English Bay and Burrard Inlet. It features the Seawall, a 8.8-kilometer path for walking, jogging, cycling, and rollerblading that offers stunning views of the city skyline, mountains, and ocean. Other attractions include the Vancouver Aquarium (Canada\'s largest aquarium), the Totem Poles (a collection of First Nations totem poles), Brockton Point Lighthouse, Lost Lagoon (a lake with a fountain and bird sanctuary), Beaver Lake, and the Stanley Park Pavilion. The park also has beaches (Second Beach and Third Beach), tennis courts, a pitch and putt golf course, and a miniature train. The park is home to over 500,000 trees, some as old as 1,000 years. It\'s a beloved retreat for locals and a must-visit for tourists.', 'localisation' => '49.3000, -123.1400', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1501594907352-04cda38ebc29?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 23, 'name' => 'Capilano Suspension Bridge', 'description' => 'The Capilano Suspension Bridge is a simple suspension bridge crossing the Capilano River in North Vancouver. The bridge is 140 meters long and 70 meters high above the river. It was first built in 1889 by George Grant Mackay, a Scottish civil engineer, and has been rebuilt several times since. The bridge is part of a private attraction called Capilano Suspension Bridge Park, which also includes the Cliffwalk (a cliffside walkway with glass floors), Treetops Adventure (a series of suspension bridges between giant Douglas fir trees), Living Forest (interpretive signs about the rainforest), Kia’palano (a First Nations cultural exhibit), and the Trading Post gift shop. The park is particularly beautiful in winter when it\'s decorated with hundreds of thousands of lights. The bridge sways as you cross, offering a thrilling experience and beautiful views of the canyon and waterfall below.', 'localisation' => '49.3400, -123.1100', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1501594907352-04cda38ebc29?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 23, 'name' => 'Granville Island', 'description' => 'Granville Island is a charming shopping and entertainment district located under the Granville Street Bridge in Vancouver. Despite its name, it\'s actually a peninsula. The island was once an industrial area but has been transformed into a vibrant destination. The main attraction is the Granville Island Public Market, a covered market with over 50 vendors selling fresh produce, seafood, meat, cheese, baked goods, artisanal foods, flowers, and crafts. Other attractions include the Net Loft (shops and services), the Kids Market (with toy stores and a play area), the Arts Club Theatre, the Granville Island Hotel, Emily Carr University of Art and Design, craft breweries (including Granville Island Brewing), art galleries, and live entertainment (including street performers and music). The island is connected to downtown by ferries (Aquabus and False Creek Ferries). It\'s a great place to shop, eat, and watch the water activity.', 'localisation' => '49.2700, -123.1300', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1501594907352-04cda38ebc29?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Quebec City (id: 24)
            ['city_id' => 24, 'name' => 'Old Quebec', 'description' => 'Old Quebec (Vieux-Québec) is the historic heart of Quebec City, a UNESCO World Heritage site. It is divided into two parts: the Upper Town (Haute-Ville) and the Lower Town (Basse-Ville). The Upper Town sits atop the Cap Diamant cliff and includes the Quebec Citadel, the Plains of Abraham, the Parliament Building, and the iconic Château Frontenac hotel. The Lower Town is along the St. Lawrence River and includes the historic Petit-Champlain district (with narrow cobblestone streets, stone buildings, and shops), Place Royale (the birthplace of French civilization in North America), the Notre-Dame-des-Victoires Church, and the Musée de la Civilisation. The two towns are connected by stairs (including the Breakneck Steps) and a funicular. Old Quebec is the only walled city north of Mexico, with 4.6 kilometers of fortifications. The area is known for its European charm, French-Canadian culture, and beautiful architecture.', 'localisation' => '46.8100, -71.2100', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1506619216599-9d16d0903dfd?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 24, 'name' => 'Château Frontenac', 'description' => 'Château Frontenac is a historic hotel in Quebec City that has become the city\'s most iconic landmark. The hotel is located in the Upper Town, atop the Cap Diamant cliff, overlooking the St. Lawrence River. The château was designed by American architect Bruce Price and built by the Canadian Pacific Railway between 1892 and 1893. The hotel is a prime example of Châteauesque architecture (also known as Canadian Château style), featuring turrets, towers, and a copper roof. The hotel is named after Louis de Buade, Count of Frontenac, who was governor of New France. The hotel has hosted many famous guests, including Queen Elizabeth II, Winston Churchill, Franklin D. Roosevelt, and Alfred Hitchcock (who filmed scenes from "I Confess" there). Visitors can take guided tours of the hotel, dine at one of its restaurants, or simply admire the exterior. The hotel is especially beautiful when illuminated at night.', 'localisation' => '46.8100, -71.2100', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1506619216599-9d16d0903dfd?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 24, 'name' => 'Montmorency Falls', 'description' => 'Montmorency Falls is a spectacular waterfall at the mouth of the Montmorency River, located about 12 kilometers from Quebec City. The falls are 83 meters high, making them 30 meters higher than Niagara Falls. The falls are part of Montmorency Falls Park (Parc de la Chute-Montmorency), which also includes a suspension bridge over the falls, a cable car to the top, staircases to the bottom, a zipline, and a Via Ferrata (climbing route). The falls are particularly impressive in winter when the spray freezes into a large cone of ice at the base (called the "Sugarloaf"), and the park offers ice climbing. The falls are illuminated at night. The park also has picnic areas, walking trails, and a restaurant. The falls are named by Samuel de Champlain in 1613 after Henri II, Duke of Montmorency. The park is a popular day trip from Quebec City for nature lovers.', 'localisation' => '46.8800, -71.1400', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1506619216599-9d16d0903dfd?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // ==================== MOROCCO (City IDs 25-27) ====================
            // Marrakech (id: 25)
            ['city_id' => 25, 'name' => 'Jemaa el-Fnaa', 'description' => 'Jemaa el-Fnaa is Marrakech\'s main square and marketplace, a UNESCO Masterpiece of Oral and Intangible Heritage of Humanity. The square is the heart of Marrakech\'s medina and comes alive at night with storytellers, musicians, dancers, snake charmers, monkey handlers, fortune tellers, and food stalls. During the day, the square is filled with orange juice stalls and vendors. The square has been a gathering place for centuries, serving as a site for public executions, trade, and entertainment. The name means "Assembly of the Dead" in Arabic, possibly referring to the public executions. The square is surrounded by souks (markets), cafes (with rooftop terraces for viewing the square), the Koutoubia Mosque (the largest mosque in Marrakech), and the Marrakech Museum. The square is most atmospheric at dusk and into the evening when the food stalls are set up and the entertainment begins.', 'localisation' => '31.6200, -7.9900', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1489749798305-4fea3ae63d43?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 25, 'name' => 'Bahia Palace', 'description' => 'The Bahia Palace is a stunning 19th-century palace in Marrakech, built between 1866 and 1867 by Si Moussa, the grand vizier of Sultan Hassan I, and expanded by his son, Ahmed ben Moussa. The name "Bahia" means "brilliance" or "beauty." The palace was designed to be the greatest palace of its time, with 150 rooms, beautiful courtyards, gardens, and intricate decorations. Highlights include the Grand Courtyard (with a long reflecting pool), the Little Courtyard (with a central fountain and intricate zellij tilework), the Court of Honor (with orange trees), the private apartments of Ahmed ben Moussa, the harem (with 40 rooms), and the large gardens. The palace features stunning examples of Moroccan craftsmanship, including carved cedar wood, painted ceilings, stained glass, and zellij (mosaic tilework). The palace is partially furnished and decorated to show how it looked in the 19th century. It\'s one of Marrakech\'s most visited attractions.', 'localisation' => '31.6200, -7.9800', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1489749798305-4fea3ae63d43?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 25, 'name' => 'Majorelle Garden', 'description' => 'The Majorelle Garden (Jardin Majorelle) is a stunning botanical garden and artist\'s landscape garden in Marrakech. The garden was created by French painter Jacques Majorelle over a period of 40 years starting in 1923. The garden features a distinctive vibrant blue (known as "Majorelle Blue") on the buildings and structures. The garden is home to hundreds of plant species from five continents, including cacti, palms, bamboo, water lilies, and bougainvillea. The garden also features fountains, pools, and paths. In 1980, the garden was bought by fashion designers Yves Saint-Laurent and Pierre Bergé, who restored it. The garden contains the Berber Museum (Musée Berbère), housed in the former studio of Jacques Majorelle, which displays Berber art, textiles, jewelry, and artifacts. There is also a memorial to Yves Saint-Laurent (his ashes were scattered in the garden). The garden is a peaceful oasis in the heart of busy Marrakech.', 'localisation' => '31.6400, -8.0000', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1489749798305-4fea3ae63d43?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Sahara Desert (id: 26)
            ['city_id' => 26, 'name' => 'Erg Chebbi Dunes', 'description' => 'Erg Chebbi is a large sea of sand dunes in the Sahara Desert, located near the town of Merzouga in southeastern Morocco. The dunes are some of the largest in Morocco, reaching heights of up to 150 meters (490 feet) and stretching for about 50 kilometers from north to south and 5 to 10 kilometers from east to west. The color of the sand varies from golden to orange to red, depending on the time of day. The dunes are popular for camel trekking (often at sunset or sunrise), sandboarding, quad biking, and camping under the stars. The area is also known for its salt flats and oasis villages. The best time to visit is from October to April when temperatures are milder. The sunset and sunrise views are spectacular, with the dunes changing color as the light shifts. The area is also good for stargazing due to minimal light pollution.', 'localisation' => '31.2000, -4.0000', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1464790719320-516ecd75af6c?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 26, 'name' => 'Merzouga', 'description' => 'Merzouga is a small desert village in southeastern Morocco, serving as the gateway to the Erg Chebbi dunes. The village is known for its traditional Berber culture, mud-brick buildings, and proximity to the Sahara Desert. The village has grown around the tourism industry, offering hotels, auberges (guesthouses), and desert camps. The area is home to a population of Berbers (Amazigh people) who have traditionally been nomadic but are now semi-nomadic or settled. The village is surrounded by the desert, salt flats (Dayet Srji), and small oasis farms growing dates and vegetables. Activities from Merzouga include camel treks into the dunes, 4x4 desert tours, sandboarding, quad biking, and overnight stays in desert camps (luxury or traditional). The area is also good for birdwatching, particularly for flamingos and other migratory birds at the salt flats. Merzouga is about a 7-hour drive from Marrakech or a 9-hour drive from Fes.', 'localisation' => '31.1000, -4.0100', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1464790719320-516ecd75af6c?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 26, 'name' => 'Desert Camp', 'description' => 'A traditional Berber desert camp in the Erg Chebbi dunes offers an authentic Sahara experience. Camps range from basic (traditional) to luxury (with private bathrooms, real beds, and electricity). Most camps are located deep in the dunes, accessible only by camel or 4x4. The experience typically includes a camel trek to the camp, a welcome with mint tea, a traditional dinner (tagine or couscous), Berber music and dancing around the campfire, and overnight in a tent. The highlight is the incredible stargazing due to minimal light pollution. Sunrise over the dunes is spectacular. Most camps have a common tent for dining and socializing, and separate sleeping tents. Some luxury camps have private tents with en-suite bathrooms, hot water, and proper beds. The experience offers a glimpse into traditional Berber nomadic life. The best time for a desert camp is October to April when temperatures are comfortable.', 'localisation' => '31.2000, -3.9800', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1464790719320-516ecd75af6c?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Chefchaouen (id: 27)
            ['city_id' => 27, 'name' => 'Blue Medina', 'description' => 'The Blue Medina is the historic center of Chefchaouen, famous for its buildings painted in various shades of blue. The tradition of painting buildings blue is believed to have started in the 1930s by Jewish refugees who believed that blue represented heaven and reminded them of God. The blue is traditionally made from a natural powder (chalk or limestone). Today, the medina is a maze of narrow, winding streets (derbs) lined with blue-washed buildings, shops, and houses. The most photogenic streets are often the ones off the main thoroughfares, where the blue is most intense. The medina is divided into three sections: the Upper Medina (north), the Lower Medina (south), and the main square (Plaza Uta el-Hammam). The medina is home to the Grand Mosque (built in the 15th century), the Kasbah Museum (a 15th-century fortress with gardens and a tower), and many shops selling local handicrafts (woolen garments, woven blankets, and leather goods).', 'localisation' => '35.1700, -5.2700', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1547489432-cf93fa6c71ee?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 27, 'name' => 'Ras El Maa Waterfall', 'description' => 'Ras El Maa Waterfall is a small waterfall on the edge of Chefchaouen\'s medina, located where the Ras El Maa River meets the city. The name "Ras El Maa" means "Source of Water" in Arabic. The waterfall is a popular spot for locals to wash clothes, socialize, and cool off. The water is cold and clean, coming from the mountains. The area around the waterfall is surrounded by blue-washed buildings and has several cafes. Visitors can walk behind the waterfall, dip their feet in the water, or simply watch the local life. The waterfall is particularly beautiful in spring when the water flow is strongest. It\'s a peaceful spot away from the busy medina streets. The waterfall is located at the northern edge of the medina, near the Bab el-Ain gate. The path to the waterfall offers views of the mountains and the city. It\'s a great spot for photography, especially in the morning light.', 'localisation' => '35.1700, -5.2700', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1547489432-cf93fa6c71ee?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 27, 'name' => 'Spanish Mosque', 'description' => 'The Spanish Mosque (Mosquita) is an abandoned mosque located on a hill overlooking Chefchaouen, offering spectacular panoramic views of the blue city and the surrounding Rif Mountains. The mosque was built in the 1920s by the Spanish during their occupation of northern Morocco but was never completed and has never been used for prayers. The name "Spanish Mosque" is a misnomer, as it\'s actually a church that was intended to be converted into a mosque. The building is in ruins, with only the walls and minaret remaining. The hike to the mosque takes about 30-45 minutes from the medina, uphill but not too strenuous. The views from the mosque are best at sunset when the city glows in golden light. The mosque is a popular spot for watching the sunset and taking photographs of the city below. The hike passes through fields and offers views of the surrounding mountains.', 'localisation' => '35.1800, -5.2700', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1547489432-cf93fa6c71ee?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // ==================== SPAIN (City IDs 28-30) ====================
            // Barcelona (id: 28)
            ['city_id' => 28, 'name' => 'Sagrada Família', 'description' => 'The Sagrada Família is Barcelona\'s most iconic landmark, a magnificent Roman Catholic basilica designed by the famous Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí. Construction began in 1882 and continues to this day, with completion expected in 2026 (the centenary of Gaudí\'s death). The basilica is Gaudí\'s masterpiece, combining Gothic and Art Nouveau forms with his unique organic style inspired by nature. The church has 18 towers, representing the 12 Apostles, the 4 Evangelists, the Virgin Mary, and Jesus Christ (the tallest, at 172.5 meters). The facades are richly decorated: the Nativity Facade (east), the Passion Facade (west), and the Glory Facade (south). The interior is like a forest, with tree-like columns branching at the top to support the ceiling, and colorful stained glass creating a magical light. The Sagrada Família is a UNESCO World Heritage site and one of the most visited monuments in Spain.', 'localisation' => '41.4036, 2.1744', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1539037116277-4db20889f2d4?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 28, 'name' => 'Park Güell', 'description' => 'Park Güell is a public park system composed of gardens and architectural elements located on Carmel Hill in Barcelona. The park was designed by Antoni Gaudí and built between 1900 and 1914. It was originally intended as a housing development for wealthy families but was later converted into a municipal park. The park is a UNESCO World Heritage site and one of Gaudí\'s most colorful works. Highlights include the Dragon Stairway (with the famous mosaic salamander, a symbol of Barcelona), the Hypostyle Room (a hall with 86 Doric columns), the Greek Theatre (or Nature Square, with a serpentine bench covered in trencadís mosaics), the Austria Gardens (with views of Barcelona), and the Gaudí House Museum (where Gaudí lived for 20 years). The park offers stunning views of Barcelona and the Mediterranean Sea. It\'s a whimsical and magical place, especially beautiful in the morning light.', 'localisation' => '41.4138, 2.1528', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1539037116277-4db20889f2d4?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 28, 'name' => 'Las Ramblas', 'description' => 'Las Ramblas is a famous tree-lined pedestrian boulevard in central Barcelona, stretching 1.2 kilometers from Plaça de Catalunya to the Christopher Columbus monument at Port Vell. The boulevard is actually a series of shorter streets: Rambla de Canaletes, Rambla dels Estudis, Rambla de Sant Josep (also known as Rambla de les Flors), Rambla dels Caputxins, and Rambla de Santa Mònica. Las Ramblas is known for its lively atmosphere, street performers (living statues), flower stalls, souvenir shops, cafes, and restaurants. The boulevard is also home to important buildings including the Gran Teatre del Liceu (opera house), the Mercat de la Boqueria (famous food market), the Palau de la Virreina (exhibition center), and the Font de Canaletes (a fountain where Barcelona fans celebrate victories). Las Ramblas is a must-see for visitors but is also known for pickpocketing, so caution is advised. It\'s at its most atmospheric in the evening.', 'localisation' => '41.3800, 2.1700', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1539037116277-4db20889f2d4?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Ibiza (id: 29)
            ['city_id' => 29, 'name' => 'Cala Comte Beach', 'description' => 'Cala Comte (also called Platja de Comte) is one of Ibiza\'s most beautiful beaches, located on the west coast of the island near Sant Josep de sa Talaia. The beach is known for its stunning turquoise water, golden sand, and spectacular sunsets. The beach is actually several small coves (calas) divided by rocky outcrops. The water is crystal clear and generally calm, making it excellent for swimming and snorkeling. The beach has sunbed and umbrella rentals, lifeguards, showers, and a parking area. There are several restaurants and beach bars (chiringuitos), including the famous Sunset Ashram, known for its sunset views and chill-out music. The beach faces west, offering direct sunset views over the islands of Es Vedrà, Es Vedranell, and S\'Espartar. Cala Comte is popular but less crowded than some other Ibiza beaches, especially outside July and August. It\'s a great spot for a relaxing day and beautiful sunset photos.', 'localisation' => '38.9500, 1.2100', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1519651150555-9d3c3c2c7e0a?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 29, 'name' => 'Dalt Vila', 'description' => 'Dalt Vila (meaning "High Town" in Catalan) is the historic fortified old town of Ibiza Town, a UNESCO World Heritage site. The area is surrounded by 16th-century Renaissance walls built by King Philip II of Spain to protect against pirate attacks. Dalt Vila sits on a hill overlooking the Mediterranean Sea and the modern part of the city. Highlights include the Portal de ses Taules (the main gate, with bronze statues and a drawbridge), the Catedral de la Mare de Déu de les Neus (the 14th-century cathedral), the Castell d\'Eivissa (the castle at the highest point), the Museo Arqueológico (archaeological museum with Phoenician artifacts), the Plaza de la Vila (the main square, with restaurants and cafes), and the winding cobblestone streets lined with white-washed buildings, flowers, and boutiques. The views from the top are spectacular, especially at sunset. Dalt Vila is also the setting for the medieval festival and other cultural events.', 'localisation' => '38.9100, 1.4300', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1519651150555-9d3c3c2c7e0a?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 29, 'name' => 'Café del Mar', 'description' => 'Café del Mar is a legendary bar and chill-out venue located in Sant Antoni de Portmany on the west coast of Ibiza. The bar opened in 1980 and became famous for its spectacular sunset views and its pioneering chill-out music. The bar was the birthplace of the "Balearic Beat" and "chill-out" music genres, and its music compilations (Café del Mar series) became internationally famous. The bar is built on a concrete platform over the water, with seating facing west for optimal sunset viewing. The atmosphere is relaxed, with soft music, comfortable seating, and drinks (cocktails, wine, beer, and non-alcoholic options). The bar is particularly famous for the DJ sets timed to coincide with the sunset. Café del Mar is a bucket-list destination for electronic music fans and sunset lovers. It\'s best to arrive early to secure a seat, especially in peak season. The bar also has a restaurant and a shop selling branded merchandise and music.', 'localisation' => '38.9800, 1.3000', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1519651150555-9d3c3c2c7e0a?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Seville (id: 30)
            ['city_id' => 30, 'name' => 'Real Alcázar', 'description' => 'The Real Alcázar of Seville is a stunning royal palace originally developed by Moorish Muslim kings. It\'s considered one of the most beautiful examples of Mudéjar architecture (Islamic art adapted for Christian purposes) in Spain. The palace is still used by the Spanish royal family as their official residence in Seville, making it the oldest royal palace still in use in Europe. The palace complex includes several buildings, courtyards, and gardens built over different periods (from the 11th to the 16th centuries). Highlights include the Patio de las Doncellas (Courtyard of the Maidens), the Salón de Embajadores (Hall of Ambassadors, with its stunning gold dome), the Patio de las Muñecas (Courtyard of the Dolls), the Baños de Doña María de Padilla (rainwater cisterns), and the extensive gardens with fountains, pavilions, and tropical plants. The Alcázar was featured as the Water Gardens of Dorne in the TV series Game of Thrones. It\'s a UNESCO World Heritage site.', 'localisation' => '37.3841, -5.9912', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1513442542250-521d6ff5f6bf?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 30, 'name' => 'Seville Cathedral', 'description' => 'Seville Cathedral (Catedral de Santa María de la Sede) is the largest Gothic cathedral in the world and the third-largest church overall (after St. Peter\'s in Vatican City and St. Paul\'s in London). The cathedral was built between 1401 and 1506 on the site of the city\'s main mosque, which had been built by the Almohads in the 12th century. The cathedral incorporates elements of the original mosque, including the Giralda (the former minaret, now a bell tower) and the Patio de los Naranjos (Courtyard of Oranges). Highlights include the main altarpiece (the largest in the world, with 44 carved scenes from the life of Christ), the tomb of Christopher Columbus (held aloft by four kings), the choir with its 15th-century stalls, the Sacristía Mayor (with art by Goya and Murillo), and the Giralda tower (with 35 ramps instead of stairs, designed for guards on horseback). The cathedral is a UNESCO World Heritage site.', 'localisation' => '37.3859, -5.9932', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1513442542250-521d6ff5f6bf?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 30, 'name' => 'Plaza de España', 'description' => 'Plaza de España is a magnificent square in Seville\'s Parque de María Luisa, built for the Ibero-American Exposition of 1929. The square is a masterpiece of Regionalist architecture, a blend of Renaissance Revival, Neo-Mudéjar, and Art Deco styles. The square is semicircular (representing Spain\'s embrace of its former colonies), with a building lining the curve and a canal in front (representing Spain\'s maritime history). The building has 48 alcoves (tiled benches) representing the 48 provinces of Spain, each with a map, historical scenes, and coat of arms. The square features two towers at the ends, bridges over the canal, and a central fountain. The square is decorated with colorful azulejos (painted ceramic tiles) depicting historical events. The square has been used as a filming location for movies including "Lawrence of Arabia" (1962) and "Star Wars: Attack of the Clones" (2002). Visitors can rent rowboats on the canal. It\'s most beautiful at sunset.', 'localisation' => '37.3770, -5.9870', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1513442542250-521d6ff5f6bf?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 31, 'name' => 'Oia Sunset', 'description' => 'The sunset in Oia is world-famous and considered one of the most beautiful sunsets on the planet. Oia is a picturesque village on the northern tip of Santorini, known for its white-washed buildings, blue-domed churches, and stunning caldera views. Every evening, hundreds of visitors gather on the castle ruins, the main pedestrian street, and the rooftops to watch the sun sink into the Aegean Sea. As the sun sets, the sky turns shades of orange, pink, and purple, and the white buildings glow golden. The moment the sun dips below the horizon, the crowd often applauds. The sunset is particularly spectacular because of the caldera\'s unique geography, with the sun setting directly behind the volcanic islands. To get the best spots, arrive at least an hour early. The sunset is also beautiful from a boat tour, offering a different perspective.', 'localisation' => '36.4619, 25.3754', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1533105079780-92b9be482077?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 31, 'name' => 'Red Beach', 'description' => 'Red Beach (Kokkini Paralia) is one of Santorini\'s most famous and unique beaches, located near the ancient site of Akrotiri. The beach gets its name from the dramatic red and black volcanic cliffs that surround it, creating a stunning contrast with the deep blue Aegean Sea. The red color comes from iron-rich volcanic rocks and lava. The beach is relatively small, with coarse red and black sand and pebbles. The water is deep and clear, excellent for snorkeling. Access to the beach requires a short hike (about 10-15 minutes) from the parking area, including a steep section and walking along a rocky path. The hike offers spectacular views of the beach and the surrounding cliffs. There are no facilities directly on the beach (except for a small seasonal canteen), so bring water and snacks. The beach can be crowded in summer, so arrive early. The cliffs are unstable in some areas, so be cautious of falling rocks.', 'localisation' => '36.3514, 25.3886', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1533105079780-92b9be482077?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 31, 'name' => 'Ancient Thera', 'description' => 'Ancient Thera is an archaeological site located on the top of Mesa Vouno mountain, between the beaches of Kamari and Perissa. The city was founded in the 9th century BCE by Dorian colonists from Sparta and was continuously inhabited until the Byzantine era. The site offers stunning panoramic views of the Aegean Sea, the island of Santorini, and the neighboring islands. Highlights include the Agora (marketplace), the Sanctuary of Artemidoros (with rock-cut inscriptions and symbols), the Temple of Apollo Karneios (the city\'s main temple), the Theater (built in the 2nd century BCE, with 1,500 seats), the Roman Baths (with mosaic floors), the Terrace of the Festivals (with inscriptions), and the early Christian Basilica. The site also includes a cemetery, houses, and a cistern. The hike up to the site is steep but rewarding. The site is less crowded than other Santorini attractions, offering a peaceful experience and a glimpse into ancient life.', 'localisation' => '36.3636, 25.4781', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1533105079780-92b9be482077?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Athens (id: 32)
            ['city_id' => 32, 'name' => 'Acropolis', 'description' => 'The Acropolis of Athens is the most important ancient site in the Western world, a UNESCO World Heritage site, and the symbol of ancient Greek civilization. The Acropolis (meaning "high city") is a flat-topped rock rising 156 meters above sea level, visible from almost everywhere in Athens. The site contains several ancient buildings of great architectural and historical significance, the most famous being the Parthenon. The Acropolis was inhabited as early as the Neolithic period and became a religious center in the 6th century BCE. Other structures include the Propylaea (the monumental gateway), the Temple of Athena Nike (dedicated to Athena as goddess of victory), and the Erechtheion (with its famous Porch of the Caryatids, six female statues serving as columns). The Acropolis Museum at the base houses artifacts found on the site. The best time to visit is early morning or late afternoon to avoid heat and crowds.', 'localisation' => '37.9715, 23.7257', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1514041181368-bca62cceffcd?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 32, 'name' => 'Parthenon', 'description' => 'The Parthenon is the most famous building on the Acropolis and one of the most recognizable landmarks in the world. It was built between 447 and 438 BCE during the Golden Age of Athens under the leadership of Pericles, designed by architects Ictinus and Callicrates, with sculptures supervised by the sculptor Phidias. The Parthenon was dedicated to Athena Parthenos (Athena the Virgin), the patron goddess of Athens. It housed a massive gold and ivory statue of Athena. The building is a masterpiece of Doric architecture, with 8 columns at the ends and 17 on the sides. The sculptures (the pediments, metopes, and the frieze) depicted Greek myths and the Panathenaic procession. The Parthenon has survived as a temple, a church, a mosque, and a powder magazine (it was damaged by a Venetian cannonball in 1687). Restoration work continues today. The Parthenon is a symbol of democracy, philosophy, and Western civilization.', 'localisation' => '37.9715, 23.7265', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1514041181368-bca62cceffcd?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 32, 'name' => 'Plaka', 'description' => 'Plaka is the oldest neighborhood in Athens, located at the base of the Acropolis. Known as the "Neighborhood of the Gods," Plaka has been continuously inhabited for over 3,500 years. The area is a maze of narrow, winding cobblestone streets lined with neoclassical buildings, shops, cafes, tavernas, and historic sites. Highlights include the Roman Agora (including the Tower of the Winds), the Ancient Agora (including the Temple of Hephaestus, the best-preserved ancient Greek temple), Hadrian\'s Library, the Lysicrates Monument, the Museum of Greek Folk Art, and the Frissiras Museum (contemporary art). Plaka is also home to Anafiotika, a small neighborhood of white-washed, Cycladic-style houses built by workers from the island of Anafi in the 19th century. Plaka is popular for souvenir shopping, especially for leather goods, jewelry, and art. It\'s at its most atmospheric in the evening when the tavernas have live music and the streets are lit.', 'localisation' => '37.9700, 23.7300', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1514041181368-bca62cceffcd?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Crete (id: 33)
            ['city_id' => 33, 'name' => 'Knossos Palace', 'description' => 'The Palace of Knossos is the largest and most famous Minoan archaeological site, located about 5 kilometers south of Heraklion, Crete. It was the ceremonial and political center of the Minoan civilization, Europe\'s first advanced civilization, which flourished from 2700 to 1450 BCE. The palace is associated with the myth of the Minotaur (the half-man, half-bull creature) and the Labyrinth (the maze where the Minotaur was kept). The palace covered about 20,000 square meters and had over 1,300 rooms on multiple levels, organized around a central courtyard. Highlights include the Throne Room (with the alabaster throne and frescoes of griffins), the Grand Staircase (with light wells), the Queen\'s Megaron (with a dolphin fresco), the storage rooms (with giant pithoi jars), and the theater area. The palace was excavated and partially reconstructed by Sir Arthur Evans in the early 20th century. The reconstruction is controversial but helps visitors visualize the original appearance.', 'localisation' => '35.2980, 25.1630', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1531605703851-e1a8cd0c4a48?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 33, 'name' => 'Elafonissi Beach', 'description' => 'Elafonissi Beach is one of Crete\'s most beautiful and unique beaches, located on the southwestern tip of the island. The beach is famous for its pink sand, created by crushed seashells (especially foraminifera) mixing with the white sand. The pink color is most visible in the early morning and late afternoon. Elafonissi is actually a lagoon with shallow turquoise water that rarely exceeds one meter in depth, making it safe for children and ideal for wading. The beach is divided by a small sandbar that leads to a small island (Elafonissi island), which is a protected nature reserve. The area is protected as a Natura 2000 site, home to rare plants (including the endemic Cretan date palm) and wildlife. Facilities include sunbed rentals, umbrellas, a few canteens, and parking. The beach is located about 75 kilometers from Chania and can be reached by car or tour bus. It\'s very popular, so arrive early in summer to secure a spot.', 'localisation' => '35.2711, 23.5317', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1531605703851-e1a8cd0c4a48?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 33, 'name' => 'Samaria Gorge', 'description' => 'The Samaria Gorge is one of Europe\'s longest and most spectacular gorges, located in the White Mountains of western Crete. The gorge is 16 kilometers long and is part of Samaria National Park, a UNESCO Biosphere Reserve. The hike from the entrance at Xyloskalo (1,250 meters elevation) to the exit at Agia Roumeli (on the Libyan Sea) takes 4 to 7 hours, depending on fitness level. Highlights include the "Gates of Hell" (the narrowest section, only 3-4 meters wide with walls 300 meters high), the church of Agios Nikolaos (built into a cave), the abandoned village of Samaria (with its church and stone houses), and the crystal-clear river with natural pools for swimming. The gorge is home to the endangered Cretan wild goat (kri-kri), which can sometimes be spotted. The best time to hike is from May to October (closed in winter). Bring sturdy shoes, water, snacks, sun protection, and a flashlight. The exit at Agia Roumeli has beach and ferry connections to other towns.', 'localisation' => '35.2700, 23.9700', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1531605703851-e1a8cd0c4a48?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // ==================== NEW ZEALAND (City IDs 34-36) ====================
            // Queenstown (id: 34)
            ['city_id' => 34, 'name' => 'Skyline Queenstown', 'description' => 'Skyline Queenstown is a gondola that takes visitors to the summit of Bob\'s Peak, offering spectacular panoramic views of Queenstown, Lake Wakatipu, The Remarkables mountain range, and the surrounding Southern Alps. The gondola is steep, rising 450 meters to an elevation of 790 meters. At the summit, activities include the Luge (a gravity-driven three-wheeled cart on a winding track, suitable for all ages), mountain biking (with trails down the mountain), and the Stratosfare Restaurant (buffet dining with floor-to-ceiling windows). The Skyline complex also includes a bar, gift shop, and the Kiwi Haka cultural performance (Maori dance). The gondola operates year-round, but winter offers stunning snow-capped mountain views. Sunset is the most popular time, offering golden light and the chance to see the town lights below. The Skyline is also the starting point for the Queenstown Trail (hiking and biking). The Luge is a family favorite, with different tracks for beginners and advanced riders.', 'localisation' => '-45.0300, 168.6600', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1507699622108-4be3abd695ad?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 34, 'name' => 'Milford Sound', 'description' => 'Milford Sound is a stunning fjord in Fiordland National Park, part of the Te Wahipounamu UNESCO World Heritage site. Despite its name, Milford Sound is actually a fjord (a valley carved by glaciers and flooded by the sea). It was described by Rudyard Kipling as the "eighth wonder of the world." The fjord stretches 15 kilometers and is surrounded by sheer rock cliffs rising 1,200 meters from the water. Highlights include Mitre Peak (1,692 meters), the highest mountain rising directly from the sea; Lady Bowen Falls (162 meters, the highest waterfall in the fjord); Stirling Falls (155 meters); and the Fairy Falls. The fjord is home to fur seals, dolphins, penguins (Fiordland crested penguins), and occasionally whales. The best way to experience Milford Sound is by boat cruise, which goes to the Tasman Sea and back. The drive to Milford Sound from Queenstown is also spectacular, passing through rainforests, mountains, and the Homer Tunnel. The area receives up to 7 meters of rain annually, creating temporary waterfalls.', 'localisation' => '-44.6700, 167.9200', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1507699622108-4be3abd695ad?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 34, 'name' => 'Shotover River', 'description' => 'The Shotover River is a famous river in the Otago region of the South Island, known for its gold-mining history and white-water jet boating. The river flows through the dramatic Shotover Canyon, with steep schist rock walls. The river was the site of a gold rush in the 1860s, and remnants of mining can still be seen. The most popular activity is jet boating, invented by Sir William Hamilton in the 1960s. Shotover Jet (the original) takes visitors on a thrilling 25-minute ride through the canyon, performing 360-degree spins and skimming past rock walls with only centimeters to spare. The boats reach speeds of up to 85 kilometers per hour. Other activities include white-water rafting (grades 3-5), gold panning, and hiking along the river. The river is also part of the Queenstown Trail for biking. The Shotover River is a must-do for adrenaline seekers visiting Queenstown. The jet boat ride is suitable for most ages, but you will get wet.', 'localisation' => '-45.0200, 168.6300', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1507699622108-4be3abd695ad?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Rotorua (id: 35)
            ['city_id' => 35, 'name' => 'Te Puia', 'description' => 'Te Puia is a geothermal valley and Maori cultural center in Rotorua, home to the famous Pohutu Geyser, the largest active geyser in the Southern Hemisphere. Pohutu erupts up to 20 times per day, reaching heights of up to 30 meters (100 feet). The valley also features other geothermal features, including boiling mud pools (mud pools), hot springs, silica terraces, and steaming vents. Te Puia is also home to the New Zealand Maori Arts and Crafts Institute, where visitors can see traditional carving (wood, bone, and stone) and weaving (flax) being taught. The center offers guided tours, cultural performances (including the haka, poi dances, and songs), and a traditional hangi meal (food cooked in a geothermal steam box). Te Puia also has a kiwi house (with nocturnal kiwis) and a living Maori village (Whakarewarewa). The geothermal area has strong cultural significance to the local Te Arawa iwi (tribe). The sulfur smell (rotten eggs) is strong but part of the experience.', 'localisation' => '-38.1600, 176.2500', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516156008625-3a9d6067fab5?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 35, 'name' => 'Wai-O-Tapu', 'description' => 'Wai-O-Tapu is a geothermal wonderland located about 25 kilometers south of Rotorua, known for its colorful hot springs and unique geothermal features. The name "Wai-O-Tapu" means "Sacred Waters" in Maori. The main attraction is the Champagne Pool, a large hot spring with orange, green, and purple terraces, named for its constant stream of carbon dioxide bubbles (like champagne). The pool is 65 meters in diameter and 62 meters deep, with a temperature of 74°C. The colors come from minerals: orange from antimony and arsenic, green from iron, purple from manganese, and yellow from sulfur. Other highlights include the Artist\'s Palette (a series of colorful pools), the Devil\'s Bath (bright green from high sulfur content), the Devil\'s Ink Pots (black mud pools), and the Bridal Veil Falls (a waterfall over silica terraces). The Lady Knox Geyser erupts daily at 10:15 AM (induced by soap), reaching heights of 10-20 meters. The park has walking trails (30 minutes to 1.5 hours).', 'localisation' => '-38.3500, 176.3800', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516156008625-3a9d6067fab5?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 35, 'name' => 'Polynesian Spa', 'description' => 'The Polynesian Spa is a world-famous hot springs spa located on the shores of Lake Rotorua. The spa has 28 mineral hot pools (with varying temperatures from 36°C to 42°C), fed by two different natural hot springs: the Priest Spring (acidic, known for relieving aches and pains) and the Rachel Spring (alkaline, known for its skin benefits). The spa has three main areas: the Deluxe Lake Pools (with views of Lake Rotorua and the best facilities), the Pavilion Pools (covered, with four pools), and the Family Pools (shallow, for children). The spa also offers a range of treatments, including massage, facials, body wraps, and the "Geothermal Mud Bath" (using Rotorua mud). The spa has a cafe, a gift shop, and changing rooms. The pools are open late (until 11 PM), offering a relaxing experience under the stars. The spa is particularly popular at sunset, when the pools offer views of the setting sun over the lake. It\'s a perfect way to unwind after a day of exploring geothermal wonders.', 'localisation' => '-38.1300, 176.2500', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516156008625-3a9d6067fab5?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Auckland (id: 36)
            ['city_id' => 36, 'name' => 'Sky Tower', 'description' => 'The Sky Tower is Auckland\'s most iconic landmark, a telecommunications and observation tower standing 328 meters tall (the tallest freestanding structure in the Southern Hemisphere). The tower opened in 1997 and is part of the SkyCity entertainment complex (casino, hotel, restaurants, theater). The tower has three observation levels: the Main Observation Level (186 meters, with 360-degree views, interactive exhibits, and glass floors), the Sky Lounge (190 meters, with a cafe), and the Orbit Revolving Restaurant (190 meters, rotates 360 degrees every hour). The views extend up to 80 kilometers on clear days, including the Hauraki Gulf, the Waitakere Ranges, and the city. For adrenaline seekers, the SkyWalk allows visitors to walk around the 1.2-meter-wide platform at 192 meters (without handrails), and the SkyJump is a controlled base jump (a 192-meter cable-controlled jump). The tower is illuminated at night in different colors for special events. It\'s a must-visit for first-time visitors to Auckland.', 'localisation' => '-36.8484, 174.7624', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1507699622108-4be3abd695ad?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 36, 'name' => 'Waiheke Island', 'description' => 'Waiheke Island is a beautiful island in the Hauraki Gulf, just a 35-40 minute ferry ride from downtown Auckland. The island is known for its stunning beaches, vineyards, olive groves, and artistic community. Waiheke has over 20 vineyards and wineries, many with cellar doors and restaurants offering stunning sea views (including Stonyridge, Mudbrick, and Cable Bay). The island also has beautiful beaches, including Oneroa Beach (the main beach), Onetangi Beach (the longest, 2.5 kilometers), and Little Oneroa Beach (quieter). Other activities include hiking (the Te Ara Hura trail is 45 kilometers around the island), mountain biking, kayaking, stand-up paddleboarding, art gallery visits (Waiheke has a thriving artist community), and the Waiheke Community Art Gallery. The main town is Oneroa, with shops, cafes, and restaurants. Waiheke is a popular day trip from Auckland, but overnight stays allow a more relaxed experience. The island\'s motto is "It\'s five o\'clock somewhere," reflecting its relaxed vibe.', 'localisation' => '-36.8000, 175.1000', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1507699622108-4be3abd695ad?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 36, 'name' => 'Auckland Domain', 'description' => 'The Auckland Domain is the city\'s oldest and largest park, a 75-hectare public park located on the site of a dormant volcano (Pukekawa, meaning "hill of bitter memories"). The park was established in 1840, making it older than the city itself. The Domain is home to the Auckland War Memorial Museum, a neoclassical building on the highest point of the park, with exhibits on New Zealand history, Maori and Pacific Island culture, natural history, and war memorials. The park also features the Wintergardens (two large glasshouses with tropical and temperate plants, plus a courtyard with statues and a pond), the Domain Wintergardens Fernery (with ferns), the Duck Pond (with waterfowl), and the Cenotaph (war memorial). The park has walking and jogging trails, sports fields, tennis courts, a playground, and picnic areas. The park is particularly beautiful in spring when the cherry blossoms bloom. The Domain is also used for concerts and events, including the annual Auckland Lantern Festival. It\'s a green oasis in the heart of the city.', 'localisation' => '-36.8600, 174.7700', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1507699622108-4be3abd695ad?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // ==================== EGYPT (City IDs 37-39) ====================
            // Cairo (id: 37)
            ['city_id' => 37, 'name' => 'Pyramids of Giza', 'description' => 'The Pyramids of Giza are the last surviving wonder of the ancient world, located on the Giza Plateau about 18 kilometers southwest of Cairo. The complex includes three main pyramids: the Great Pyramid of Khufu (Cheops), the Pyramid of Khafre (Chephren), and the Pyramid of Menkaure (Mycerinus). The Great Pyramid was built around 2560 BCE and was the tallest man-made structure in the world for over 3,800 years, standing at 146.5 meters originally (now 138.8 meters). It is estimated to have been built with 2.3 million stone blocks, weighing an average of 2.5 tons each. The pyramids were built as tombs for the pharaohs and are aligned with the stars of Orion\'s Belt. Visitors can enter the Great Pyramid (limited tickets, can be claustrophobic) and see the Grand Gallery and the King\'s Chamber. The site also includes several smaller pyramids (for queens), boat pits (with the reconstructed Khufu Solar Boat), and the Giza Plateau offers spectacular views, especially at sunset. The pyramids are a UNESCO World Heritage site.', 'localisation' => '29.9792, 31.1342', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1503177119275-0aa32b3a9368?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 37, 'name' => 'Sphinx', 'description' => 'The Great Sphinx of Giza is a massive limestone statue of a mythical creature with the body of a lion and the head of a human (believed to be Pharaoh Khafre). The Sphinx is located on the Giza Plateau, near the Pyramids of Giza. It is the largest monolith statue in the world, measuring 73.5 meters long, 20.2 meters high, and 19.3 meters wide. The Sphinx was carved around 2500 BCE and is believed to have been built to guard the pyramids and the Giza Plateau. Over the centuries, the Sphinx has been buried in sand several times, with the most recent excavation in the 1920s-1930s. The nose is missing (popular myth attributes this to Napoleon\'s soldiers, but it was actually broken off by a Sufi Muslim in the 14th century). Between the paws is the Dream Stele, a granite slab placed by Pharaoh Thutmose IV, who dreamed that the Sphinx promised him kingship if he cleared away the sand. The Sphinx is a symbol of ancient Egyptian civilization and one of the world\'s most famous statues.', 'localisation' => '29.9753, 31.1377', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1503177119275-0aa32b3a9368?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 37, 'name' => 'Egyptian Museum', 'description' => 'The Egyptian Museum (Museum of Egyptian Antiquities) in Cairo\'s Tahrir Square is home to the world\'s largest collection of ancient Egyptian artifacts, with over 120,000 items on display. The museum was built in 1901 in a neoclassical style and has two floors. The most famous exhibit is the treasures of Tutankhamun, including his solid gold death mask (weighing 11 kilograms), his three coffins (the innermost made of 110 kilograms of solid gold), his golden throne, jewelry, chariots, and other funerary objects. Other highlights include the Royal Mummy Room (with the mummies of 11 pharaohs, including Ramses II and Seti I, requires separate ticket), the Narmer Palette (one of the earliest historical documents, dating to 3100 BCE), the statues of Khafre and Menkaure, the collection of papyrus, the jewelry, and the animal mummies (including cats, crocodiles, and birds). The museum is overcrowded and poorly labeled, so a guide is recommended. A new museum, the Grand Egyptian Museum (GEM), is being built near the Giza Pyramids and will eventually replace this museum.', 'localisation' => '30.0478, 31.2333', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1503177119275-0aa32b3a9368?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Hurghada (id: 38)
            ['city_id' => 38, 'name' => 'Giftun Island', 'description' => 'Giftun Island is a protected national park and one of the most popular day trip destinations from Hurghada, known for its pristine beaches, crystal-clear turquoise water, and excellent snorkeling and diving. The island is actually two islands: Giftun Kebir (Big Giftun) and Giftun Soraya (Little Giftun). Giftun Kebir is the most visited, with a beautiful sandy beach, coral reefs, and shallow lagoons. The island has no permanent structures (except for a few basic facilities), preserving its natural beauty. The coral reefs around the island are home to hundreds of species of colorful fish, sea turtles, rays, and other marine life. The water is calm and clear, with visibility often exceeding 20 meters. Snorkeling trips typically include equipment, lunch, and soft drinks. The island is accessible only by boat (about 30-45 minutes from Hurghada). There are no toilets or changing facilities, so be prepared. The best time to visit is early morning to avoid crowds and heat. Giftun Island is a paradise for beach and snorkeling lovers.', 'localisation' => '27.1800, 33.9800', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1562693266-5a3b8ab84114?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 38, 'name' => 'Mahmya Beach', 'description' => 'Mahmya Beach is a private beach and eco-tourism destination on the southern tip of Giftun Island, offering a more upscale and less crowded experience than other Hurghada beaches. The name "Mahmya" means "protected area" in Arabic, reflecting its status as part of a national park. The beach features powdery white sand, clear turquoise water, and excellent snorkeling on the surrounding coral reefs. Mahmya Beach is operated as a day-use facility with sunbeds, umbrellas, a restaurant (serving buffet lunch), a bar, showers, changing rooms, and toilets. The beach also offers water sports (kayaking, paddleboarding, pedal boats) and glass-bottom boat tours. The atmosphere is relaxed and family-friendly. Access is by boat (about 45 minutes from Hurghada) and requires a reservation (day packages). The number of visitors is limited to protect the environment, so it\'s less crowded than public beaches. Mahmya Beach is a perfect choice for those seeking a more comfortable and exclusive beach experience. The sunset views from the beach are spectacular.', 'localisation' => '27.1800, 33.9800', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1562693266-5a3b8ab84114?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 38, 'name' => 'Red Sea Aquarium', 'description' => 'The Red Sea Aquarium (also known as Hurghada Grand Aquarium) is a modern marine museum and aquarium located about 5 kilometers north of Hurghada. The aquarium is part of the Sindbad Resort complex. It features 24 galleries representing different marine environments of the Red Sea, with over 1,200 species of marine life, including sharks, rays, sea turtles, moray eels, lionfish, clownfish, and many colorful reef fish. Highlights include the Shark Tunnel (an underwater tunnel where sharks and rays swim overhead), the Touch Tank (where visitors can touch starfish, sea cucumbers, and other safe marine creatures), the Jellyfish Gallery (with illuminated jellyfish), the Amazon Rainforest exhibit (with freshwater fish and reptiles), and the outdoor area with crocodiles, turtles, and snakes. The aquarium also has a gift shop and a cafe. The aquarium is educational and entertaining for all ages, and it\'s a good activity for a hot day or as a break from the beach. It\'s less well-known than snorkeling trips, so it\'s generally not crowded.', 'localisation' => '27.2300, 33.8300', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1562693266-5a3b8ab84114?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Luxor (id: 39)
            ['city_id' => 39, 'name' => 'Valley of the Kings', 'description' => 'The Valley of the Kings is a UNESCO World Heritage site and one of the world\'s most important archaeological sites, located on the west bank of the Nile opposite Luxor. The valley was used as a royal burial ground for pharaohs of the New Kingdom (16th-11th centuries BCE) for nearly 500 years. It contains 63 tombs and chambers, including the famous tomb of Tutankhamun (KV62, discovered by Howard Carter in 1922). The tombs are cut into the limestone rock and decorated with scenes from ancient Egyptian religious texts (the Book of the Dead, the Book of Gates, etc.). The most impressive tombs include Ramses VI (KV9, with intact decorations), Seti I (KV17, the longest and most decorated), Ramses III (KV11, with harpist scenes), and Thutmose III (KV34, with the Amduat text). The valley is divided into the East Valley (where most tombs are located) and the West Valley (less visited). Photography is not allowed in the tombs. The standard ticket allows entry to three tombs (excluding Tutankhamun and some others, which require separate tickets). The valley is hot, so visit early morning. The site also has a visitor center and a cafeteria.', 'localisation' => '25.7400, 32.6000', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1564257631407-4deb1f99d992?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 39, 'name' => 'Karnak Temple', 'description' => 'Karnak Temple is the largest religious complex ever built, covering over 200 acres (80 hectares), and one of the most visited sites in Egypt. It was the main place of worship for the Theban Triad (Amun, Mut, and Khonsu) and was built, expanded, and modified over 1,500 years (from the Middle Kingdom to the Ptolemaic period). The complex includes the Precinct of Amun-Re (the largest and most accessible), the Precinct of Mut, the Precinct of Montu, and the Temple of Amenhotep IV (dismantled). Highlights include the Great Hypostyle Hall (with 134 massive columns, the largest weighing 70 tons, 21 meters high), the Avenue of Sphinxes (connecting Karnak to Luxor Temple), the Obelisk of Hatshepsut (29.5 meters tall, one of the largest in Egypt), the Obelisk of Thutmose I, the Sacred Lake (used for rituals), the Festival Temple of Thutmose III, the Chapels of Sekhmet, and the Temple of Ramses III. The sound and light show in the evening brings the temple to life. Karnak is a testament to the power and ambition of ancient Egyptian pharaohs.', 'localisation' => '25.7187, 32.6573', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1564257631407-4deb1f99d992?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 39, 'name' => 'Luxor Temple', 'description' => 'Luxor Temple is a large ancient Egyptian temple complex located on the east bank of the Nile in the heart of modern Luxor. It was built primarily by Amenhotep III (14th century BCE) and expanded by Ramses II (13th century BCE). Unlike other temples, Luxor Temple was not dedicated to a god or a deceased pharaoh but to the rejuvenation of kingship and the Opet Festival (when the statues of Amun, Mut, and Khonsu traveled from Karnak to Luxor). The temple is particularly beautiful at night when illuminated. Highlights include the First Pylon (24 meters high, built by Ramses II, with reliefs of his Battle of Kadesh), the Obelisk of Ramses II (the other obelisk is in Paris\'s Place de la Concorde), the Great Colonnade (with 14 columns, 19 meters high), the Court of Ramses II (with double row of columns and statues), the Court of Amenhotep III (with double row of papyrus columns), the Barque Shrine (where the sacred boat rested), and the Roman frescoes (from the 3rd century CE when the temple was used as a Roman military camp and church). The temple is connected to Karnak by the Avenue of Sphinxes (recently reopened after restoration).', 'localisation' => '25.6995, 32.6395', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1564257631407-4deb1f99d992?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // ==================== MEXICO (City IDs 40-42) ====================
            // Cancun (id: 40)
            ['city_id' => 40, 'name' => 'Chichen Itza', 'description' => 'Chichen Itza is the most famous Mayan archaeological site, located in Mexico\'s Yucatán Peninsula. It was designated one of the New Seven Wonders of the World in 2007 and is a UNESCO World Heritage site. The site was a major Mayan city from 600-1200 CE and shows a mix of Mayan and Toltec architecture. The most iconic structure is El Castillo (the Temple of Kukulcán), a pyramid with 365 steps (one for each day of the year). During the spring and autumn equinoxes, the sun creates a serpent shadow descending the pyramid. Other structures include the Great Ball Court (the largest in Mesoamerica, 168 meters long), the Temple of Warriors (with hundreds of columns), the Group of a Thousand Columns, the Sacred Cenote (a natural sinkhole used for sacrifices), the Observatory (El Caracol, used for astronomical observations), and the Las Monjas (a complex of buildings with Puuc architecture). The site also has a cenote (Ik Kil) nearby where visitors can swim. Chichen Itza is a must-see for visitors to Mexico, but it\'s crowded, so arrive early.', 'localisation' => '20.6843, -88.5678', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516307365426-bea591f05011?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 40, 'name' => 'Isla Mujeres', 'description' => 'Isla Mujeres (Island of Women) is a small island in the Caribbean Sea, located about 13 kilometers east of Cancun. The island is known for its beautiful beaches, crystal-clear turquoise water, and laid-back atmosphere. The main beach, Playa Norte (North Beach), is consistently ranked as one of the best beaches in Mexico, with powdery white sand and shallow, calm water. The island is only 7 kilometers long and 650 meters wide, easily explored by golf cart (the main form of transportation), scooter, or bicycle. Highlights include the Punta Sur (the southern tip, with a Mayan temple dedicated to the goddess Ixchel, a lighthouse, and a sculpture garden), the Tortugranja (a sea turtle farm and conservation center), the Garrafon Natural Reef Park (for snorkeling, zip-lining, and kayaking), the Underwater Museum of Art (MUSA, with submerged sculptures), and the Hacienda Mundaca (the ruins of a pirate\'s estate). The island is a popular day trip from Cancun (ferry takes 15-30 minutes), but overnight stays allow a more relaxed experience.', 'localisation' => '21.2300, -86.7300', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516307365426-bea591f05011?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 40, 'name' => 'Xcaret Park', 'description' => 'Xcaret Park is an eco-archaeological park located about 75 kilometers south of Cancun, in the Riviera Maya. The park is set in a natural jungle with underground rivers, cenotes, beaches, and a zoo. Activities include swimming and floating in underground rivers (the park has 900 meters of underground rivers), snorkeling in cenotes and the Caribbean Sea, zip-lining, and swimming with dolphins (extra cost). The park also has cultural attractions, including a Mayan village (with replica Mayan houses and a ball court), a butterfly pavilion (with hundreds of butterflies), an orchid nursery (with over 100 species), a jaguar island (with jaguars, pumas, and ocelots), a bat cave (with bats and crocodiles), and a coral reef aquarium (with live coral and tropical fish). The highlight is the evening show, "Xcaret Mexico Espectacular," a 2-hour show with over 300 performers showcasing Mexican history, music, and dance (including the Voladores de Papantla, mariachi, and Day of the Dead). Xcaret is a full-day experience, and the park is very popular, so book in advance.', 'localisation' => '20.5800, -87.1200', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516307365426-bea591f05011?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Mexico City (id: 41)
            ['city_id' => 41, 'name' => 'Teotihuacan', 'description' => 'Teotihuacan is an ancient Mesoamerican city located about 50 kilometers northeast of Mexico City, known as the "City of the Gods." It was one of the largest cities in the ancient world, at its peak (150-450 CE) covering 20 square kilometers with a population of 125,000-200,000. The site is a UNESCO World Heritage site. The main attractions are the Pyramid of the Sun (the third-largest pyramid in the world, 65 meters tall, 225 meters at the base), the Pyramid of the Moon (43 meters tall), and the Temple of the Feathered Serpent (Quetzalcoatl, with 200 feathered serpent heads). The site also includes the Avenue of the Dead (the main thoroughfare, 2.5 kilometers long), the Citadel (a large plaza), and the Palace of the Jaguars (with murals). Visitors can climb the pyramids (the Pyramid of the Sun has 248 steps) for spectacular views. The site also has a museum with artifacts (including models and murals). Teotihuacan\'s influence extended throughout Mesoamerica, but its culture and rulers remain unknown. The name Teotihuacan means "the place where the gods were created" in Nahuatl.', 'localisation' => '19.6900, -98.8400', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1512813195386-60cf811b74a2?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 41, 'name' => 'Frida Kahlo Museum', 'description' => 'The Frida Kahlo Museum (Museo Frida Kahlo), also known as the Blue House (Casa Azul), is the former home of the famous Mexican artist Frida Kahlo and her husband, muralist Diego Rivera. The museum is located in the Coyoacán neighborhood of Mexico City. The house, painted bright blue, was where Kahlo was born (1907), lived most of her life, and died (1954). The museum houses personal belongings, photographs, letters, clothing, jewelry, and some of her paintings, including "Viva la Vida" (Long Live Life) and "Frida and the Cesarean." The museum also has a recreation of her studio, the kitchen, and the garden. The house has been preserved as it was during her life. Highlights include the bed where she painted (with a mirror attached to the canopy so she could paint self-portraits while bedridden), her collection of pre-Hispanic art, and her colorful traditional Tehuana dresses. The museum is very popular, with long lines (book tickets in advance online). The Coyoacán neighborhood is charming, with cobblestone streets, cafes, and markets.', 'localisation' => '19.3550, -99.1620', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1512813195386-60cf811b74a2?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 41, 'name' => 'Zocalo', 'description' => 'The Zócalo, formally known as Plaza de la Constitución, is the main square in Mexico City and one of the largest city squares in the world (240 meters x 240 meters). It is the political and cultural heart of Mexico. The square is surrounded by three important buildings: the National Palace (Palacio Nacional), the Metropolitan Cathedral (Catedral Metropolitana), and the Old City Hall (Antiguo Palacio del Ayuntamiento). The National Palace is the seat of the federal executive, with murals by Diego Rivera depicting Mexican history, including the famous "The History of Mexico." The Metropolitan Cathedral is the largest cathedral in the Americas, built between 1573 and 1813, combining Gothic, Baroque, Neoclassical, and other styles. The square also has the Templo Mayor, the main temple of the Aztec capital Tenochtitlan (discovered in 1978, now an archaeological site and museum). The Zócalo hosts major events, including Independence Day celebrations (September 15-16), concerts (from rock bands to opera), political rallies, and art installations. It\'s a vibrant, essential Mexico City experience.', 'localisation' => '19.4326, -99.1332', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1512813195386-60cf811b74a2?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Chichen Itza (id: 42)
            ['city_id' => 42, 'name' => 'El Castillo', 'description' => 'El Castillo (The Castle), also known as the Temple of Kukulcán, is the most famous and iconic structure at Chichen Itza. This step pyramid was built by the Mayans between the 9th and 12th centuries CE. The pyramid has 9 levels, 4 sides, and 365 steps (91 steps on each side plus the top platform), representing the 365 days of the solar year. Each side has 18 terraces (representing the 18 months of the Mayan calendar). The pyramid is 24 meters high (30 meters including the temple). During the spring and autumn equinoxes (March 20-21 and September 21-22), the sun creates a shadow of a serpent descending the pyramid\'s north staircase, representing the feathered serpent god Kukulcán. The pyramid was built over an earlier, smaller pyramid (accessible through a tunnel, revealing a red jaguar throne with jade eyes). The pyramid is acoustically remarkable: a clap in front of the staircase creates a sound echoing like the quetzal bird. Visitors can no longer climb the pyramid (closed after a fatal fall in 2006), but it remains the centerpiece of Chichen Itza.', 'localisation' => '20.6829, -88.5686', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516307365426-bea591f05011?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 42, 'name' => 'Cenote Ik Kil', 'description' => 'Cenote Ik Kil is a beautiful open-air cenote (natural sinkhole) located near Chichen Itza, about 3 kilometers from the archaeological site. The cenote is 60 meters in diameter, 40 meters deep (of which about 26 meters is water), and has a water depth of 40 meters. The cenote is surrounded by lush vegetation, with vines and small waterfalls dropping from the opening 26 meters above the water. The water is clear and cool (about 26°C), with small catfish. The cenote was considered sacred by the Mayans, used for human sacrifice (artifacts and bones have been found at the bottom). Today, it\'s a popular swimming spot. Facilities include changing rooms, lockers, showers, life jackets, and a restaurant. There are stairs down to a swimming platform, and some jumping points. The cenote is part of the Ik Kil Archaeological Park, which also includes a small Mayan museum, a chapel, and a snack bar. It\'s a refreshing stop after visiting Chichen Itza (especially in hot weather). The best time to visit is early morning or late afternoon to avoid crowds.', 'localisation' => '20.6800, -88.5700', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516307365426-bea591f05011?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 42, 'name' => 'Temple of Warriors', 'description' => 'The Temple of Warriors (Templo de los Guerreros) is a large stepped pyramid complex at Chichen Itza, named for the carved columns depicting warriors. The temple was built between 900-1100 CE and shows strong Toltec influence. The complex includes the Temple of Warriors (with a Chac Mool statue at the top, a reclining figure holding a bowl for offerings), the Group of a Thousand Columns (a large plaza with 200 columns representing warriors, which once supported a roof), the Temple of the Jaguars (with a jaguar throne and murals), and the Market (a colonnaded building). The columns are carved with bas-reliefs of warriors, priests, and deities, offering insights into Mayan and Toltec rituals. The complex was likely used for ceremonies, meetings, and as a market. The Temple of Warriors is similar in design to the Temple of the Warriors at Tula (the Toltec capital), demonstrating the cultural exchange between the Mayans and Toltecs. The complex is impressive in scale and detail, and it\'s one of the highlights of Chichen Itza. Visitors cannot climb the temple for safety reasons.', 'localisation' => '20.6830, -88.5690', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516307365426-bea591f05011?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // ==================== GERMANY (City IDs 43-45) ====================
            // Berlin (id: 43)
            ['city_id' => 43, 'name' => 'Brandenburg Gate', 'description' => 'The Brandenburg Gate (Brandenburger Tor) is Berlin\'s most famous landmark and a symbol of German unity. The neoclassical gate was built between 1788 and 1791 by King Frederick William II of Prussia, designed by Carl Gotthard Langhans, inspired by the Propylaea of the Acropolis in Athens. The gate has 12 Doric columns (6 on each side), forming 5 passageways. On top is the Quadriga, a statue of the goddess of victory (Victoria) driving a four-horse chariot, designed by Johann Gottfried Schadow. During the Cold War, the gate stood in East Berlin, just behind the Berlin Wall, becoming a symbol of division. When the wall fell in 1989, the gate became a symbol of German reunification. The gate was restored in 2000-2002. The gate is located on Pariser Platz, with the Reichstag building to the north, the Memorial to the Murdered Jews of Europe to the south, and the Tiergarten park to the west. The gate is especially beautiful at night when illuminated. It\'s a must-visit for any visitor to Berlin.', 'localisation' => '52.5163, 13.3777', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1467269204594-9661b134dd2b?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 43, 'name' => 'Berlin Wall', 'description' => 'The Berlin Wall was a guarded concrete barrier that divided Berlin from 1961 to 1989, separating East Berlin (communist) from West Berlin (democratic). The wall was 155 kilometers long (43 kilometers dividing the city) and included guard towers, bunkers, and a "death strip" with rakes, dogs, and tripwires. At least 140 people died trying to cross. The wall fell on November 9, 1989, leading to German reunification. Today, the most famous remaining section is the East Side Gallery, a 1.3-kilometer stretch of the wall (the longest remaining section) along the Spree River in Friedrichshain. The wall is covered with 105 murals by artists from around the world, painted in 1990, including Dmitri Vrubel\'s "Fraternal Kiss" (Brezhnev kissing Honecker) and Birgit Kinder\'s "Test the Best" (a Trabant car breaking through the wall). Other memorial sites include the Berlin Wall Memorial at Bernauer Strasse (with a preserved section of the wall, the death strip, and a documentation center) and the Checkpoint Charlie Museum (about the famous crossing point between East and West).', 'localisation' => '52.5020, 13.4400', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1467269204594-9661b134dd2b?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 43, 'name' => 'Reichstag Building', 'description' => 'The Reichstag Building is the home of the German parliament (Bundestag), a historic building with a modern glass dome designed by architect Norman Foster. The building was completed in 1894 and housed the Imperial Diet (Reichstag) until 1933, when it was severely damaged by a fire (the Reichstag fire, which the Nazis used to consolidate power). The building was further damaged during WWII and was left unused during the Cold War. After reunification, the building was renovated and the glass dome was added (completed in 1999). The dome is 23 meters high and 40 meters in diameter, with a spiral ramp leading to the top, offering 360-degree views of Berlin. The dome is a symbol of transparency, allowing visitors to look down into the parliamentary chamber. The dome also has a solar tracking shade and a conical mirror system for natural light. The building is open to the public (free but requires registration in advance). The inscription "Dem Deutschen Volke" (To the German People) on the facade dates to 1916. The Reichstag is a symbol of German democracy and resilience.', 'localisation' => '52.5186, 13.3760', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1467269204594-9661b134dd2b?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Munich (id: 44)
            ['city_id' => 44, 'name' => 'Marienplatz', 'description' => 'Marienplatz (Mary\'s Square) is the central square in Munich, the city\'s heart since 1158. The square is dominated by the Neues Rathaus (New Town Hall), a magnificent Gothic Revival building built between 1867 and 1909. The Rathaus is famous for its Glockenspiel (carillon), which reenacts two stories daily at 11 AM and 12 PM (and 5 PM in summer): the wedding of Duke Wilhelm V in 1568 (with a jousting tournament) and the Schäfflertanz (coopers\' dance) from 1517. The Glockenspiel has 43 bells and 32 life-sized figures. The square also has the Altes Rathaus (Old Town Hall, the former city hall, now a toy museum), the Mariensäule (Mary\'s Column, built in 1638 to celebrate the end of Swedish occupation), and the Fischbrunnen (Fish Fountain, where apprentices were thrown into the fountain as a prank). Marienplatz is a pedestrian zone (since 1972) and is surrounded by shops, restaurants, and cafes. It\'s the starting point for exploring Munich\'s historic center (Altstadt). The square is particularly beautiful at Christmas, with a large Christmas market (Christkindlmarkt). It\'s always crowded, but it\'s a must-see.', 'localisation' => '48.1372, 11.5755', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1508050919630-b135583b29f4?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 44, 'name' => 'Neuschwanstein Castle', 'description' => 'Neuschwanstein Castle is a 19th-century Romanesque Revival palace on a rugged hill in the Bavarian Alps, near Füssen in southwest Bavaria. The castle was commissioned by King Ludwig II of Bavaria (known as the "Fairytale King") as a retreat and a homage to Richard Wagner, the composer. Construction began in 1869 but was never completed; Ludwig died in 1886 (only 17 rooms were finished). The castle opened to the public shortly after his death and has since become one of Germany\'s most popular tourist destinations, inspiring Disney\'s Sleeping Beauty Castle. The castle has over 60 rooms, decorated with scenes from Wagner\'s operas (including Tannhäuser, Lohengrin, and Parsifal). Highlights include the Throne Room (with a Byzantine-style apse and a painting of Jesus), the Singers\' Hall (inspired by the Wartburg Castle), the Grotto (an artificial cave with a waterfall), and Ludwig\'s bedroom (with 14 carpenters working for 4.5 years on the wood carvings). The views of the surrounding mountains, lakes, and valleys are spectacular. The castle is accessible by bus, horse-drawn carriage, or a 30-minute uphill walk.', 'localisation' => '47.5576, 10.7498', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1508050919630-b135583b29f4?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 44, 'name' => 'English Garden', 'description' => 'The English Garden (Englischer Garten) is one of the world\'s largest urban parks, larger than New York\'s Central Park (375 hectares vs. 340 hectares). The park was created in 1789 by Sir Benjamin Thompson (Count Rumford) and was one of the first public parks in Europe. The park stretches from the city center to the northeastern suburbs, following the Isar River. Highlights include the Chinese Tower (Chinesischer Turm), a 25-meter wooden pagoda built in 1790 (the current one is a 1952 reconstruction), surrounded by a beer garden (one of Munich\'s largest, seating 7,000); the Monopteros (a Greek-style temple on a hill, offering views of the city); the Japanese Teahouse (a gift from Tokyo); the Kleinhesseloher See (a lake with paddle boats and a beer garden); and the Eisbach (a man-made river with a standing wave, famous for river surfing, even in winter). The park is popular for walking, jogging, cycling, picnicking, sunbathing (including nude sunbathing in designated areas), and drinking beer at the beer gardens. It\'s a beloved escape for locals and visitors alike.', 'localisation' => '48.1500, 11.5900', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1508050919630-b135583b29f4?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Black Forest (id: 45)
            ['city_id' => 45, 'name' => 'Triberg Falls', 'description' => 'Triberg Falls (Triberger Wasserfälle) is one of Germany\'s highest waterfalls, located in the Black Forest near the town of Triberg. The falls have a total drop of 163 meters over 7 steps. The water cascades down granite rocks, creating a beautiful and dramatic scene. The falls are illuminated at night (until 10 PM) for a magical effect. Visitors can view the falls from several viewing platforms connected by paths and stairs. The best time to visit is in spring (May-June) when the snowmelt creates the highest water volume. The falls are accessible year-round, but in winter, the water freezes into ice formations. The falls are part of a nature reserve, surrounded by forest. The area also has a Black Forest Museum (Schwarzwaldmuseum), a German Clock Museum (Deutsches Uhrenmuseum), and the world\'s largest cuckoo clock (in Triberg, actually a building shaped like a cuckoo clock). The town of Triberg is also known for its traditional Black Forest costumes and for being the home of the cuckoo clock (invented here in 1738).', 'localisation' => '48.1300, 8.2300', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1506182982230-38fdefcef3a8?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 45, 'name' => 'Lake Titisee', 'description' => 'Lake Titisee is a beautiful glacial lake in the Black Forest, located near the town of Titisee-Neustadt. The lake is about 1.2 kilometers long and 0.8 kilometers wide, with a maximum depth of 40 meters. It was formed by the Feldberg glacier during the last ice age. The lake is surrounded by forested hills and offers stunning scenery. Activities include swimming (the water is clean but cold), boating (paddle boats, rowboats, electric boats, and small sailboats), stand-up paddleboarding, fishing, and hiking around the lake (about 6.5 kilometers). In winter, the lake often freezes, allowing ice skating and ice sailing. The town of Titisee-Neustadt is known for its cuckoo clock shops (including the House of 1000 Clocks), Black Forest cake (Schwarzwälder Kirschtorte), and spas. The lake is a popular day trip from Freiburg (30 minutes by train) and is busy in summer. The best time for photos is early morning when the water is calm and reflective. The lake is also a starting point for hiking in the Black Forest.', 'localisation' => '47.8900, 8.1500', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1506182982230-38fdefcef3a8?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 45, 'name' => 'Cuckoo Clock Shops', 'description' => 'The Black Forest is the traditional home of the cuckoo clock, invented in the village of Schönwald in 1738 by Franz Anton Ketterer. Today, the region is filled with cuckoo clock shops, particularly in the towns of Triberg, Titisee-Neustadt, and Furtwangen. The most famous is the House of 1000 Clocks (Haus der 1000 Uhren) in Titisee, with a giant cuckoo clock on the facade. The German Clock Museum (Deutsches Uhrenmuseum) in Furtwangen has the world\'s largest collection of clocks, including the first cuckoo clocks. Cuckoo clocks are still made in the traditional way, with hand-carved wooden cases (usually depicting Black Forest scenes: deer, birds, leaves, hunters, or chalets) and mechanical movements. The cuckoo bird appears and calls on the hour and half-hour (the number of calls indicates the time). Some clocks also have music boxes or moving figures. Shops offer demonstrations, repairs, and worldwide shipping. Buying a cuckoo clock is a classic Black Forest souvenir, but be prepared for high prices (authentic ones cost several hundred euros). Cheaper, battery-operated versions are also available.', 'localisation' => '48.1300, 8.2300', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1506182982230-38fdefcef3a8?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            ['city_id' => 46, 'name' => 'Table Mountain', 'description' => 'Table Mountain is Cape Town\'s most iconic landmark, a flat-topped mountain rising 1,086 meters above the city. The mountain is part of the Table Mountain National Park and is one of the New7Wonders of Nature. The flat top (3 kilometers long) is often covered by a "tablecloth" of clouds, a phenomenon caused by the wind. The mountain offers spectacular views of Cape Town, Table Bay, Robben Island, the Cape Peninsula, and the Atlantic Ocean. Visitors can reach the summit by the Table Mountain Aerial Cableway (which rotates 360 degrees during the 5-minute ride) or by hiking (over 500 routes, with Platteklip Gorge being the most direct). At the summit, visitors can walk along the Dassie Loop (named for the rock hyraxes, locally called dassies), visit the shop and restaurant, or hike to other peaks. The cableway was first built in 1929 and has been upgraded several times. The mountain is home to over 2,200 species of plants (many endemic) and diverse wildlife, including dassies, lizards, snakes, and tortoises. The best time to visit is in summer (November to March) when the cableway is most reliable.', 'localisation' => '-33.9628, 18.4092', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516026672322-bc52d61a55d5?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 46, 'name' => 'Cape of Good Hope', 'description' => 'The Cape of Good Hope is a rocky headland on the Atlantic coast of the Cape Peninsula, often mistakenly thought to be the southernmost point of Africa (that\'s Cape Agulhas, 150 kilometers southeast). However, it is a significant landmark: the first European to reach it was Bartolomeu Dias in 1488, and it marked the point where ships began to travel east. The cape is part of the Table Mountain National Park, a UNESCO World Heritage site (Cape Floral Region). The area offers dramatic scenery, with rugged cliffs, crashing waves, fynbos vegetation (unique to the Cape), and diverse wildlife, including baboons, ostriches, antelopes (bontebok, eland), and tortoises. The Cape of Good Hope also has a lighthouse (built in 1859, now a viewing point), a funicular (the Flying Dutchman, 90 meters to the lighthouse), and a sign marking the point. Visitors can walk to the cliff edge, hike, or take a boat to see seals and dolphins. The area is also famous for the legend of the Flying Dutchman, a ghost ship. The Cape of Good Hope is a must-see for any visitor to Cape Town, offering stunning scenery and a sense of history.', 'localisation' => '-34.3586, 18.4719', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516026672322-bc52d61a55d5?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 46, 'name' => 'Robben Island', 'description' => 'Robben Island is a UNESCO World Heritage site located in Table Bay, about 12 kilometers from Cape Town. The island has been used for isolation and imprisonment since the 17th century, but it is most famous as the prison where Nelson Mandela was held for 18 of his 27 years in prison (from 1964 to 1982). Other anti-apartheid activists were also imprisoned here. The prison closed in 1991, and the island became a museum in 1997. The tour includes a ferry ride from the V&A Waterfront, a bus tour of the island (including the lime quarry where prisoners did hard labor, the leper colony, the church, and the cemetery), and a tour of the maximum-security prison led by a former political prisoner (often one who was imprisoned with Mandela). The highlight is seeing Mandela\'s cell (8x7 feet, with a mat and bucket). The tour is emotional and educational, offering insights into South Africa\'s apartheid history and Mandela\'s forgiveness. The name "Robben" is Dutch for "seal" (seals live on the island). The ferry can be rough, so take seasickness medication if needed.', 'localisation' => '-33.8064, 18.3664', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516026672322-bc52d61a55d5?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Kruger National Park (id: 47)
            ['city_id' => 47, 'name' => 'Big Five Safari', 'description' => 'The Big Five Safari is the ultimate wildlife experience in Kruger National Park, named for the five most difficult animals to hunt on foot (lion, leopard, elephant, rhino, and buffalo). Today, "shooting" is with cameras, and seeing all five is a highlight for visitors. Kruger is one of the best places in Africa to see the Big Five, with large populations: over 2,000 lions, 1,000 leopards, 13,000 elephants, 5,000 rhinos (white and black), and 37,000 buffalo. The best time for game viewing is the dry winter (May to September) when animals gather around water sources. The best areas for the Big Five are the central and southern regions of the park (especially the Sabie River area). Lions are often seen on the roads, leopards in trees or near water, elephants in herds, rhinos near water, and buffalo in large herds. Safari options include self-drive (visitors can drive themselves on the park\'s 2,500 kilometers of roads), guided game drives (in open vehicles, with experienced guides, usually 3-4 hours), and overnight walks (for experienced hikers). The thrill of seeing a lion hunt or a leopard in a tree is unforgettable. Be patient, drive slowly, and listen for animal alarms.', 'localisation' => '-24.9900, 31.5900', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516026672322-bc52d61a55d5?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 47, 'name' => 'Blyde River Canyon', 'description' => 'Blyde River Canyon is the third-largest canyon in the world (after the Grand Canyon in the USA and the Fish River Canyon in Namibia) and the largest green canyon (with lush subtropical vegetation). It is located in the Mpumalanga province, on the Panorama Route, near Kruger National Park. The canyon is 26 kilometers long, up to 1,400 meters deep, and is part of the Drakensberg escarpment. The name "Blyde" means "joy" in Dutch, referring to the joy of the Voortrekkers who escaped death. Highlights include the Three Rondavels (three huge rock formations resembling traditional African huts, named after a chief and his wives), Bourke\'s Luck Potholes (cylindrical potholes carved by water in the Treur River), God\'s Window (a viewpoint with panoramic views over the Lowveld and Kruger National Park), and the Pinnacle (a freestanding quartzite rock). Activities include hiking (the canyon has several trails), swimming in natural pools, river rafting, and abseiling. The canyon is particularly beautiful at sunrise and sunset when the colors are most vivid. The area is home to diverse wildlife, including monkeys, baboons, and birds.', 'localisation' => '-24.5500, 30.8000', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516026672322-bc52d61a55d5?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 47, 'name' => 'Panorama Route', 'description' => 'The Panorama Route is a scenic drive in Mpumalanga province, along the Drakensberg escarpment, offering spectacular views of canyons, waterfalls, and geological formations. The route is about 160 kilometers long and can be done in one day (but two days is better). The main attractions are Blyde River Canyon, the Three Rondavels, Bourke\'s Luck Potholes, God\'s Window, the Pinnacle, Lisbon Falls (94 meters, one of the highest in South Africa), Berlin Falls (45 meters, with a cylindrical shape), Mac-Mac Falls (65 meters, with a double cascade), and Pilgrim\'s Rest (a restored gold-mining town, now a living museum). The route is also famous for its views of the Lowveld and Kruger National Park. The best time to visit is in summer (October to March) when the waterfalls are flowing strongly, but the views are good year-round. The route is popular with tourists, so start early to avoid crowds. The road is paved, but some viewpoints require short walks. The Panorama Route is a beautiful complement to a safari in Kruger National Park, offering a change of scenery (mountains, forests, and waterfalls) and stunning photo opportunities.', 'localisation' => '-24.9800, 30.8500', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516026672322-bc52d61a55d5?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Johannesburg (id: 48)
            ['city_id' => 48, 'name' => 'Apartheid Museum', 'description' => 'The Apartheid Museum is a powerful and moving museum that tells the story of apartheid (1948-1994) in South Africa. The museum is located in Johannesburg, near the Gold Reef City amusement park. The entrance forces visitors to choose a race ("White" or "Non-White"), symbolizing the segregation of apartheid. The museum uses photographs, artifacts, videos, newspaper clippings, and personal testimonies to explain the rise and fall of apartheid, the struggle for freedom, and the triumph of democracy. Highlights include the exhibits on the Sharpeville Massacre (1960), the Soweto Uprising (1976), the Rivonia Trial (1963-1964), Nelson Mandela\'s imprisonment and release, and the first democratic elections in 1994. The museum also has a memorial wall with the names of those killed in the struggle. The museum is emotionally challenging but essential for understanding South Africa\'s history. The architecture is striking, with exposed concrete and brick. The museum is self-guided but audio guides are available. Allow at least 2-3 hours. The museum is a must-visit for anyone interested in history, human rights, or South Africa.', 'localisation' => '-26.2368, 28.0108', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516026672322-bc52d61a55d5?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 48, 'name' => 'Soweto', 'description' => 'Soweto (South Western Townships) is a large urban area in the City of Johannesburg, famous for its role in the anti-apartheid struggle. It was created as a township for black residents under apartheid, and it became a center of resistance. Today, Soweto is a vibrant, bustling area with a rich history, culture, and spirit. The most famous attraction is the Mandela House (8115 Vilakazi Street), the former home of Nelson Mandela (now a museum), and the Hector Pieterson Memorial (dedicated to a 13-year-old boy killed during the 1976 Soweto Uprising). Vilakazi Street is the only street in the world where two Nobel Peace Prize winners (Nelson Mandela and Desmond Tutu) lived. Other attractions include the Walter Sisulu Square (where the Freedom Charter was adopted in 1955), the Orlando Towers (former cooling towers, now used for bungee jumping, zip-lining, and rock climbing), and the Soweto Brewing Company (craft beer). The best way to experience Soweto is with a guided tour (by car, bicycle, or walking), which includes visiting a shebeen (informal bar), sampling local food (like kota or chakalaka), and meeting locals. Soweto is safe with a guide.', 'localisation' => '-26.2400, 27.8900', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516026672322-bc52d61a55d5?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 48, 'name' => 'Gold Reef City', 'description' => 'Gold Reef City is a theme park and entertainment complex in Johannesburg, built around a former gold mine (the Crown Mines). The park recreates the atmosphere of Johannesburg during the gold rush of the late 19th century, with buildings in Victorian style. Attractions include thrill rides (the Tower of Terror, the Anaconda roller coaster, the Golden Loop, and the Jozi Express), family rides, a water park (for hotel guests), and a casino. The most unique attraction is the underground mine tour (45 minutes), which descends 75 meters below the surface (220 meters when counting the slope shaft) to show how gold was mined in the 19th century, with demonstrations of drilling, blasting, and gold pouring. The park also has a museum with gold exhibits, a replica of a 19th-century street with shops and restaurants, and a hotel. Gold Reef City is popular with families and offers a fun, educational experience. The park is open daily, but the mine tours run on a schedule. The park is also home to the Apartheid Museum (next door). Gold Reef City is a good activity for a day when you\'re not on safari.', 'localisation' => '-26.2370, 28.0120', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516026672322-bc52d61a55d5?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // ==================== UNITED KINGDOM (City IDs 49-51) ====================
            // London (id: 49)
            ['city_id' => 49, 'name' => 'Big Ben', 'description' => 'Big Ben is the nickname for the Great Bell of the clock at the north end of the Palace of Westminster (the Houses of Parliament) in London. The name is often used to refer to the clock tower, which was officially renamed the Elizabeth Tower in 2012 to mark the Diamond Jubilee of Queen Elizabeth II. The tower was built in 1859 and is 96 meters tall. The clock is famous for its accuracy (it is accurate to within one second) and for the distinctive "bong" sound of the bell. The bell weighs 13.7 tons and is struck every hour. The four clock faces are 7 meters in diameter, making them the largest in the UK. Big Ben is one of London\'s most iconic landmarks and a symbol of the United Kingdom. The tower is part of a UNESCO World Heritage site (the Palace of Westminster). Visitors can tour the tower (only UK residents can apply for tours through their MP; international visitors can watch from the outside). The tower is particularly beautiful when illuminated at night. The best views are from Westminster Bridge, the London Eye, or Parliament Square. The sound of Big Ben is a quintessential London experience.', 'localisation' => '51.5007, -0.1246', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1513635269975-59663e0ac1ad?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 49, 'name' => 'Tower of London', 'description' => 'The Tower of London is a historic castle on the north bank of the River Thames, founded in 1066 as part of the Norman Conquest. It has served as a royal palace, prison, armory, treasury, menagerie (zoo), and execution site. The tower is a UNESCO World Heritage site and is famous for the Crown Jewels (the royal regalia, including crowns, scepters, and orbs, still used by the monarch). Other highlights include the White Tower (the oldest part, built by William the Conqueror, with the Line of Kings (armor and weapons)), the Bloody Tower (where the young princes were allegedly murdered), the Traitors\' Gate (where prisoners were brought by boat), the Beauchamp Tower (with prisoner graffiti), and the Medieval Palace. The tower is guarded by the Yeoman Warders (Beefeaters), who give guided tours and live on the grounds. The tower is also famous for its ravens (at least six must be kept at the tower to prevent disaster, according to legend). The Ceremony of the Keys (locking the tower each night) has taken place for 700 years. The tower is a must-visit for anyone interested in British history.', 'localisation' => '51.5081, -0.0761', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1513635269975-59663e0ac1ad?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 49, 'name' => 'British Museum', 'description' => 'The British Museum is the world\'s oldest national public museum (opened in 1759), dedicated to human history, art, and culture. It has over 8 million objects (only about 80,000 on display), covering 2 million years of history. The museum is famous for the Rosetta Stone (the key to deciphering Egyptian hieroglyphs), the Parthenon Sculptures (also known as the Elgin Marbles, from the Parthenon in Athens), the Egyptian mummies (including the mummy of Katebet), the Lewis Chessmen (12th-century chess pieces made of walrus ivory and whale teeth), the Sutton Hoo treasure (Anglo-Saxon burial artifacts), the Portland Vase (Roman cameo glass), and the Oxus Treasure (Persian gold and silver). Other highlights include the Assyrian reliefs (with winged bulls), the Lindow Man (a preserved bog body), and the Easter Island statue (Hoa Hakananai\'a). The museum\'s Great Court (opened in 2000) is the largest covered public square in Europe, with a stunning glass and steel roof designed by Norman Foster. The museum is free (special exhibitions cost extra). The museum is huge; plan to spend at least 3-4 hours, or focus on a few galleries.', 'localisation' => '51.5194, -0.1270', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1513635269975-59663e0ac1ad?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Edinburgh (id: 50)
            ['city_id' => 50, 'name' => 'Edinburgh Castle', 'description' => 'Edinburgh Castle is a historic fortress perched on Castle Rock, an extinct volcano that has been inhabited since the Iron Age. The castle dominates the Edinburgh skyline and is the most visited tourist attraction in Scotland. It served as a royal residence, military garrison, and prison. Highlights include the Crown Jewels of Scotland (the Crown, Sceptre, and Sword of State, the oldest regalia in the British Isles), the Stone of Destiny (also known as the Stone of Scone, used for the coronation of Scottish kings, returned to Scotland in 1996), the Royal Palace (with the 16th-century apartments of Mary, Queen of Scots), the Great Hall (built for James IV in 1511, with a magnificent hammerbeam roof), the National War Museum (with military history and artifacts), the Mons Meg (a giant 15th-century cannon), and the One o\'Clock Gun (fired daily at 1 PM (except Sunday) since 1861). The castle also offers stunning views of Edinburgh and the Firth of Forth. The castle is at its most dramatic during the Edinburgh Military Tattoo (August), a spectacular display of music and pageantry. Allow at least 2-3 hours.', 'localisation' => '55.9486, -3.1999', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1513635269975-59663e0ac1ad?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 50, 'name' => 'Royal Mile', 'description' => 'The Royal Mile is the historic heart of Edinburgh, a succession of streets forming the main thoroughfare of the Old Town. It runs from Edinburgh Castle (at the top) to the Palace of Holyroodhouse (at the bottom), a distance of about 1.8 kilometers (1 mile). The Royal Mile is famous for its medieval and 16th-century architecture, cobbled streets, closes (narrow alleys), and courtyards. Highlights include St. Giles\' Cathedral (the principal church of the Church of Scotland, with its famous crown steeple), the Scottish Parliament Building (the modern home of the Scottish Parliament), the High Court of Justiciary, the Real Mary King\'s Close (a preserved 17th-century street buried beneath the city, with guided tours), the Writers\' Museum (dedicated to Robert Burns, Walter Scott, and Robert Louis Stevenson), the Museum of Edinburgh (local history), John Knox House (the home of the Protestant reformer), and the Palace of Holyroodhouse (the Queen\'s official residence in Scotland). The Royal Mile is also lined with shops (selling cashmere, whisky, and souvenirs), pubs (with live folk music), restaurants, and the Edinburgh Festival Fringe venues. The atmosphere is lively and touristy, but it\'s a must-see.', 'localisation' => '55.9500, -3.1900', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1513635269975-59663e0ac1ad?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 50, 'name' => 'Arthur\'s Seat', 'description' => 'Arthur\'s Seat is the main peak of the group of hills in Holyrood Park, in the center of Edinburgh. It is an ancient volcano, formed 350 million years ago, and is 251 meters high. The name is believed to be derived from legends linking it to King Arthur. The hike to the summit takes about 30-45 minutes and is moderately strenuous (but doable for most fitness levels). The views from the top are spectacular, offering panoramic views of Edinburgh, the Firth of Forth, the Pentland Hills, and beyond. The hike passes through grassy slopes, rocky outcrops, and ancient ruins (including St. Anthony\'s Chapel, a 15th-century chapel). The park also has other peaks (including Salisbury Crags, 46 meters high, offering an easier walk). Arthur\'s Seat is a popular spot for sunrise and sunset, offering a magical light over the city. The hike is free and accessible year-round (weather permitting, as it can be windy and slippery). It\'s a great way to escape the crowds of the Royal Mile and get exercise. The best starting point is the Holyrood Palace car park. Wear sturdy shoes and bring water.', 'localisation' => '55.9440, -3.1610', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1513635269975-59663e0ac1ad?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Lake District (id: 51)
            ['city_id' => 51, 'name' => 'Lake Windermere', 'description' => 'Lake Windermere is the largest natural lake in England, 17 kilometers long, 1.6 kilometers wide, and 66 meters deep. It is located in the Lake District National Park, a UNESCO World Heritage site. The lake is surrounded by rolling hills, forests, and villages, offering stunning scenery. Activities include boat cruises (from Bowness, Ambleside, or Lakeside, ranging from 45 minutes to 3 hours), rowing, kayaking, stand-up paddleboarding, sailing, and fishing. The lake is also popular for swimming (but cold). The surrounding towns include Windermere (the largest town), Bowness-on-Windermere (the main tourist hub, with shops, restaurants, and the World of Beatrix Potter attraction), Ambleside (at the north end, with a Roman fort and waterfalls), and Lakeside (at the south end, with the Lakes Aquarium and the Haverthwaite steam railway). The lake is also a starting point for hikes, including Orrest Head (a 20-minute hike from Windermere town with panoramic views) and Wansfell Pike. The lake is beautiful in all seasons: summer for water sports, autumn for colors, winter for frosty scenes, and spring for flowers. It\'s the most popular destination in the Lake District, so it can be crowded.', 'localisation' => '54.3600, -2.9200', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1513635269975-59663e0ac1ad?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 51, 'name' => 'Scafell Pike', 'description' => 'Scafell Pike is the highest mountain in England, standing at 978 meters (3,209 feet). It is located in the Lake District National Park, and is part of the Southern Fells. The mountain is popular with hikers, and the summit offers spectacular views of the surrounding fells, lakes, and (on clear days) the Irish Sea, Scotland, and Wales. The most popular route is from Wasdale Head (the shortest and most direct, about 6 kilometers round trip, but steep and rocky, requiring 3-4 hours). Other routes include from Seathwaite (Borrowdale, longer but less steep), Eskdale, or Langdale. The terrain is rocky and can be challenging, with some scrambling. The weather can change rapidly, so hikers need proper gear (sturdy boots, waterproof clothing, map, compass, food, water) and experience. The mountain is often covered in mist, so navigation skills are important. The summit has a large cairn and an Ordnance Survey trig point. Scafell Pike is part of the National Three Peaks Challenge (climbing the highest peaks of Scotland, England, and Wales in 24 hours). The best time to climb is from May to September. The mountain is a rewarding challenge for hikers.', 'localisation' => '54.4544, -3.2116', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1513635269975-59663e0ac1ad?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 51, 'name' => 'Beatrix Potter Gallery', 'description' => 'The Beatrix Potter Gallery is a museum in Hawkshead, in the Lake District, dedicated to the life and work of Beatrix Potter (1866-1943), the author and illustrator of beloved children\'s books such as "The Tale of Peter Rabbit," "The Tale of Jemima Puddle-Duck," and "The Tale of Benjamin Bunny." The gallery is housed in a 17th-century building that was once the office of her husband, William Heelis, a solicitor. The gallery displays original watercolor illustrations by Beatrix Potter, including many of her book illustrations, as well as sketches, letters, and personal items. The gallery also tells the story of her life in the Lake District, where she became a farmer, conservationist, and sheep breeder (she was a prize-winning Herdwick sheep farmer). She left over 4,000 acres of land to the National Trust, preserving much of the Lake District. The gallery is small but charming. Nearby attractions include Hill Top (Beatrix Potter\'s farmhouse, now a museum, in Near Sawrey) and the Beatrix Potter attraction in Bowness (with 3D scenes from her books). The gallery is a must-visit for fans of Beatrix Potter and for those interested in the literary history of the Lake District.', 'localisation' => '54.3730, -2.9980', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1513635269975-59663e0ac1ad?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // ==================== TURKEY (City IDs 52-54) ====================
            // Istanbul (id: 52)
            ['city_id' => 52, 'name' => 'Hagia Sophia', 'description' => 'Hagia Sophia (Ayasofya) is a UNESCO World Heritage site and one of the most important buildings in the world, a masterpiece of Byzantine architecture. It was built as a Christian cathedral between 532 and 537 CE under Emperor Justinian I and was the world\'s largest cathedral for nearly 1,000 years. In 1453, after the Ottoman conquest, it was converted into a mosque. In 1935, it became a museum. In 2020, it was reconverted into a mosque (but remains open to visitors of all faiths). The building is famous for its massive dome (31 meters in diameter, 56 meters high), which seems to float on light (the "pendentive" design). Highlights include the mosaics (including the Deësis mosaic of Christ, the Virgin Mary, and John the Baptist; the Empress Zoe mosaic; and the Komnenos mosaic), the marble floors, the imperial doors, the Omphalion (a marble section where emperors were crowned), the Viking runic inscriptions, the minarets (added by the Ottomans), the mihrab (prayer niche), and the minbar (pulpit). The building is a symbol of the cultural and religious history of Istanbul, blending Christian and Islamic elements. The best time to visit is early morning or late afternoon to avoid crowds.', 'localisation' => '41.0085, 28.9798', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1524231757912-21f4fe3a7200?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 52, 'name' => 'Blue Mosque', 'description' => 'The Blue Mosque (Sultan Ahmed Mosque) is an active mosque in Istanbul, built between 1609 and 1616 by Sultan Ahmed I, designed by architect Sedefkâr Mehmed Ağa (a student of Mimar Sinan). It is called the Blue Mosque because of the 20,000 handmade blue Iznik tiles that decorate the interior. The mosque has six minarets (four at the corners, two at the end of the forecourt), which was controversial at the time (the only other mosque with six minarets was the Masjid al-Haram in Mecca, so the sultan added a seventh minaret to Mecca). The mosque features a large central dome (43 meters high, 23.5 meters in diameter), eight secondary domes, and a spacious courtyard. The interior is illuminated by 260 windows (originally with stained glass). Highlights include the mihrab (prayer niche) made of carved marble, the minbar (pulpit), the sultan\'s loge (a raised platform), and the beautiful chandeliers. The mosque is still used for daily prayers, so visitors should be respectful (dress code, remove shoes, no loud talking, and avoid prayer times). The mosque is particularly beautiful at sunset. The surrounding area (Sultanahmet Square) also has the Hagia Sophia, Topkapi Palace, and the Basilica Cistern.', 'localisation' => '41.0054, 28.9768', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1524231757912-21f4fe3a7200?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 52, 'name' => 'Grand Bazaar', 'description' => 'The Grand Bazaar (Kapalıçarşı) is one of the world\'s oldest and largest covered markets, located in Istanbul. It was built in 1455-1461 by Sultan Mehmed the Conqueror and has been expanded over the centuries. The bazaar covers 61 streets and 4,000 shops, attracting between 250,000 and 400,000 visitors daily. It is a maze of alleys, divided into sections for different types of goods. Shops sell carpets, textiles, leather, jewelry, ceramics, spices, Turkish delight (lokum), baklava, copperware, antiques, souvenirs, and more. Highlights include the Old Bazaar (the original section), the Sandal Bedesten (the main market, now selling antiques and carpets), the Cevahir Bedesten (the most secure section, now selling luxury goods), and the Fes and Kilim shops. The bazaar is also famous for its history, architecture (domed roofs, vaulted ceilings), and atmosphere (vendors calling out, bargaining, and offering tea). Bargaining is expected (start at half the asking price). The bazaar is crowded, so watch your belongings. The bazaar is closed on Sundays and public holidays. It\'s an experience in itself, even if you don\'t buy anything. The surrounding area also has the Spice Bazaar (Egyptian Bazaar) and the historic Grand Bazaar Hammam.', 'localisation' => '41.0100, 28.9600', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1524231757912-21f4fe3a7200?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Cappadocia (id: 53)
            ['city_id' => 53, 'name' => 'Hot Air Balloons', 'description' => 'Hot air ballooning over Cappadocia is a world-famous experience, offering breathtaking views of the region\'s unique fairy chimneys, rock formations, valleys, and cave dwellings. The balloons typically launch at sunrise (around 5-6 AM), when the winds are calmest and the light is most beautiful (golden hour). The flight lasts about 1 hour, reaching heights of 300-600 meters. The balloons carry 16-28 people in a wicker basket, divided into compartments. The pilots are experienced and licensed, and the safety record is excellent. The most popular launch sites are Göreme, Ürgüp, and Uçhisar. The flight offers views of Göreme National Park, Love Valley (with phallic-shaped formations), Pigeon Valley, Red Valley, Rose Valley, the fairy chimneys of Pasabag (Monks Valley), the castle of Uçhisar, and the villages. The landing is sometimes rough (basket on its side). The flight includes a champagne toast and a certificate. The best season is April to November, but flights occur year-round (weather permitting). Ballooning is expensive (200-300 euros per person), but it\'s a once-in-a-lifetime experience. Book in advance (months ahead for peak season). Photos from the balloon are spectacular.', 'localisation' => '38.6400, 34.8300', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1524231757912-21f4fe3a7200?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 53, 'name' => 'Göreme Open Air Museum', 'description' => 'The Göreme Open Air Museum is a UNESCO World Heritage site and one of Cappadocia\'s most important attractions, located in the Göreme Valley. The museum is a complex of rock-cut churches, chapels, and monasteries dating from the 10th to 12th centuries (the Byzantine era). The structures were carved into the soft volcanic tuff by Christian monks who sought isolation and spirituality. The most famous churches include the Dark Church (Karanlık Kilise), the best-preserved, with vivid frescoes of scenes from the New Testament (requires an extra ticket); the Apple Church (Elmalı Kilise), with frescoes of the life of Jesus; the Snake Church (Yılanlı Kilise), with frescoes of Saint George and Saint Theodore; the Sandals Church (Çarıklı Kilise), with frescoes of the Ascension; and the Buckle Church (Tokalı Kilise), the largest and oldest, with frescoes of the life of Christ. The museum also includes a nunnery, a refectory, a kitchen, and a monastery. The frescoes are remarkably well-preserved due to the dry climate. The site is crowded, so visit early morning or late afternoon. The museum is a testament to the region\'s religious history and artistic achievement.', 'localisation' => '38.6400, 34.8300', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1524231757912-21f4fe3a7200?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 53, 'name' => 'Derinkuyu Underground City', 'description' => 'Derinkuyu Underground City is one of the largest and deepest underground cities in Cappadocia, reaching a depth of 85 meters (about 18 levels), though only 8 levels are open to the public. The city was built by the Phrygians in the 8th-7th centuries BCE and was expanded by early Christians in the Byzantine era as a hiding place from persecution (from Romans, Arabs, and others). The city could hold up to 20,000 people, along with livestock and food stores. The city has ventilation shafts, wells, water channels, and a complex system of tunnels, stairs, and rooms. Highlights include the kitchen, stables, wine press, storage rooms, refectory, chapel, baptismal font, school, and tombs. The city also has a rolling stone door (a 1.5-meter diameter stone disk weighing 500 kilograms) that could be rolled across the entrance from the inside for defense. The tunnels are narrow and low, so be prepared to stoop. The city is claustrophobic for some. Derinkuyu is connected to Kaymaklı Underground City by an 8-kilometer tunnel (not open to the public). The city is a fascinating example of ancient engineering and a testament to human ingenuity and resilience.', 'localisation' => '38.3700, 34.7300', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1524231757912-21f4fe3a7200?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Pamukkale (id: 54)
            ['city_id' => 54, 'name' => 'Travertine Terraces', 'description' => 'The Travertine Terraces of Pamukkale (meaning "Cotton Castle" in Turkish) are a natural wonder, a series of white terraces formed by calcium carbonate deposits from hot springs. The hot springs (temperature 35-100°C) contain high levels of calcium bicarbonate. As the water flows down the hillside, it releases carbon dioxide, leaving behind calcium carbonate (travertine) that hardens into white terraces. The result is a stunning landscape of cascading white pools, stalactites, and terraces, creating a surreal, cotton-like appearance. Visitors can walk on the terraces (barefoot, to protect them) and bathe in the shallow pools (the water is warm and mineral-rich). The terraces are best viewed at sunset when the light creates golden and pink reflections. The site is a UNESCO World Heritage site. The terraces are fragile; visitors must follow designated paths and cannot wear shoes. The best time to visit is early morning or late afternoon to avoid crowds and heat. The terraces are also famous for the ancient city of Hierapolis above them. The combination of natural beauty and ancient history makes Pamukkale unique.', 'localisation' => '37.9200, 29.1200', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1524231757912-21f4fe3a7200?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 54, 'name' => 'Hierapolis', 'description' => 'Hierapolis was an ancient Greco-Roman city built on top of the Pamukkale travertine terraces, founded in the 2nd century BCE by the Kingdom of Pergamon. The city became a health center due to the hot springs, attracting visitors seeking healing. It was destroyed by an earthquake in 1334 and abandoned. The ruins are a UNESCO World Heritage site. Highlights include the Necropolis (one of the largest ancient cemeteries in Turkey, with over 1,200 tombs, including sarcophagi, tumuli, and house tombs), the Theater (built in the 2nd century CE, with a capacity of 12,000, well-preserved with a stage building and reliefs), the Temple of Apollo (dedicated to Apollo, with a sacred spring), the Plutonium (a cave dedicated to Pluto, god of the underworld, with toxic gases), the Frontinus Street (the main colonnaded street), the Nympheum (a monumental fountain), the Agora (marketplace), the Roman Baths (now the Hierapolis Archaeology Museum, with artifacts from the site), and the Martyrium of St. Philip (an octagonal church where the apostle Philip is believed to be buried). The site also has a well-preserved Byzantine gate. The combination of ruins and the white terraces below is spectacular.', 'localisation' => '37.9200, 29.1200', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1524231757912-21f4fe3a7200?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 54, 'name' => 'Cleopatra\'s Pool', 'description' => 'Cleopatra\'s Pool (Antique Pool) is a thermal pool within the Hierapolis archaeological site, famous for its ancient Roman columns lying in the water. The pool was formed by an earthquake in the 7th century, which caused the collapse of a Roman portico, leaving marble columns and capitals in the water. According to legend, Cleopatra herself swam in this pool (though historically, she never visited Pamukkale). The water is warm (36°C) and rich in minerals (calcium, bicarbonate, magnesium), believed to have healing properties for skin, rheumatism, and other ailments. The pool is about 4 meters deep, with the submerged columns creating a unique atmosphere. Visitors can swim among the ancient ruins (for an extra fee, not included in the main ticket). The pool is popular and can be crowded, so arrive early. Facilities include changing rooms, showers, lockers, and a cafe. The pool is open from 8 AM to 7 PM in summer. Even if you don\'t swim, it\'s worth seeing. The pool is located near the Hierapolis Theater and the museum. Swimming in Cleopatra\'s Pool is a unique experience, combining relaxation with history.', 'localisation' => '37.9200, 29.1200', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1524231757912-21f4fe3a7200?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // ==================== INDONESIA (City IDs 55-57) ====================
            // Bali (id: 55)
            ['city_id' => 55, 'name' => 'Uluwatu Temple', 'description' => 'Uluwatu Temple (Pura Luhur Uluwatu) is a Balinese Hindu temple perched on a steep cliff 70 meters above the Indian Ocean, at the southwestern tip of the Bukit Peninsula in Bali. The temple was built in the 11th century by the Javanese sage Empu Kuturan and is one of Bali\'s nine directional temples (Khayangan Jagat). It is dedicated to the spirits of the sea and protects Bali from evil. The temple is famous for its stunning location, with spectacular sunset views over the ocean. The temple is also known for its monkeys (long-tailed macaques), which are considered sacred but are also notorious for stealing visitors\' belongings (glasses, hats, phones). The temple complex includes several courtyards, pavilions, and a shrine. The entrance is a stone candi bentar (split gate). The Kecak dance (fire dance) is performed daily at sunset at a nearby amphitheater (with the temple as a backdrop), telling the story of the Ramayana. Visitors must wear a sarong and sash (available for rent). The temple is crowded at sunset, so arrive early for parking. Uluwatu is one of Bali\'s most iconic and photographed temples.', 'localisation' => '-8.8294, 115.0847', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1518548419970-58e3b4079ab2?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 55, 'name' => 'Tegalalang Rice Terraces', 'description' => 'The Tegalalang Rice Terraces are a series of stunning, lush green rice paddies located north of Ubud, Bali, part of the Subak (traditional Balinese irrigation system) UNESCO World Heritage site. The terraces follow the contour of the hill, creating a beautiful, layered landscape. The Subak system dates back to the 9th century and reflects the Balinese philosophy of Tri Hita Karana (harmony between humans, nature, and the gods). The best time to visit is early morning (for soft light and fewer crowds) or late afternoon (for golden light). Visitors can walk through the terraces (following marked paths), take photos, or visit the local farmers\' stalls selling coconuts, coffee, and souvenirs. The area also has several "swings" (giant swings over the terraces, for Instagram photos, costing extra). The terraces are most beautiful when the rice is green (just planted) or golden (ready to harvest). The schedule varies by field. Tegalalang is one of Bali\'s most photographed spots and a popular day trip from Ubud. The terraces can be crowded, so go early. There are also other rice terraces in Bali (like Jatiluwih, larger and less crowded).', 'localisation' => '-8.4350, 115.2800', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1518548419970-58e3b4079ab2?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 55, 'name' => 'Mount Batur', 'description' => 'Mount Batur (Gunung Batur) is an active volcano in the Kintamani region of Bali, standing at 1,717 meters. It is one of Bali\'s most popular trekking destinations, particularly for sunrise treks. The volcano has a caldera (a large crater) with a lake (Lake Batur) and a smaller volcano (Mount Batur I, the active cone). The trek starts around 3-4 AM (from the village of Toya Bungkah), takes 1.5-2 hours to the summit (steep and rocky, but doable for most fitness levels). At the summit (1,700 meters), you can watch the sunrise over Mount Agung (Bali\'s highest volcano) and Lake Batur, with stunning views of the caldera, the lake, and the surrounding mountains. The guides usually serve breakfast (banana sandwiches, boiled eggs) and coffee/tea at the summit. The descent takes about 1 hour. After the trek, you can visit the hot springs at the base of the volcano (Toya Devasya). The best time to trek is during the dry season (April to October). The trek is challenging for some; wear sturdy shoes, bring a headlamp (or rent one), a jacket (it\'s cold at the top), and water. The volcano is still active; the last eruption was in 2000. A guide is required (for safety).', 'localisation' => '-8.2500, 115.3700', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1518548419970-58e3b4079ab2?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Jakarta (id: 56)
            ['city_id' => 56, 'name' => 'National Monument', 'description' => 'The National Monument (Monumen Nasional, or Monas) is a 132-meter tall tower in the center of Merdeka Square, Jakarta, symbolizing the struggle for Indonesian independence. The monument was built between 1961 and 1975 under President Sukarno. The design is a yoni (rice mortar) and lingam (pestle) symbolizing fertility and harmony. The monument is topped with a 14.5-meter flame coated in 35 kilograms of gold leaf. The base houses a museum with dioramas depicting the history of Indonesia, from prehistory to independence. Visitors can take an elevator (or climb stairs) to the observation deck at 115 meters, offering panoramic views of Jakarta (though the view is often hazy). The monument is surrounded by Merdeka Square (one of the largest city squares in the world, 1 square kilometer), with fountains, gardens, and deer. The monument is open daily and is particularly beautiful at night when illuminated. The museum is educational but dated. Monas is a symbol of Indonesian pride and a must-see for first-time visitors to Jakarta. It\'s also a popular spot for local families, especially on weekends. Be prepared for crowds, security checks, and long lines for the elevator.', 'localisation' => '-6.1754, 106.8272', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1518548419970-58e3b4079ab2?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 56, 'name' => 'Istiqlal Mosque', 'description' => 'Istiqlal Mosque (Masjid Istiqlal) is the largest mosque in Southeast Asia, capable of accommodating over 120,000 worshippers. The mosque was built between 1961 and 1978 under President Sukarno, with the architect Frederich Silaban (a Christian). The name "Istiqlal" means "independence" in Arabic, symbolizing Indonesian independence. The mosque has a large central dome (45 meters in diameter, representing the year of independence, 1945), a main prayer hall (with 12 columns, representing the birth of Prophet Muhammad), and four levels of galleries (for overflow worshippers). The mosque has a single minaret (90 meters tall, representing the year of independence, 1945). The mosque is open to non-Muslim visitors (outside prayer times), with guides available. The mosque is located opposite the Jakarta Cathedral (a Catholic cathedral), symbolizing religious tolerance. Visitors must dress modestly (cover arms and legs; robes are available). The mosque is particularly impressive during Friday prayers and during Ramadan. The architecture is modern, with marble floors, geometric patterns, and good acoustics. Istiqlal is a symbol of Indonesian unity and a peaceful place to visit.', 'localisation' => '-6.1700, 106.8300', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1518548419970-58e3b4079ab2?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 56, 'name' => 'Old Town (Kota Tua)', 'description' => 'Old Town Jakarta (Kota Tua) is the historic center of Jakarta, a UNESCO World Heritage candidate, dating from the 17th century Dutch colonial era. The area was known as Batavia and was the headquarters of the Dutch East India Company (VOC). The main square is Taman Fatahillah (Fatahillah Square), surrounded by historic buildings. The most prominent is the Jakarta History Museum (Museum Sejarah Jakarta), housed in the former Batavia City Hall (built in 1707), with exhibits on Jakarta\'s history, including furniture, maps, ceramics, and the famous "Dugul" (a prison cell). Other museums include the Wayang Museum (puppets, including Javanese wayang kulit), the Fine Arts and Ceramics Museum, the Bank Indonesia Museum (money and banking), and the Bank Mandiri Museum (housed in a former bank building). The area also has a replica of the Batavia Castle (the original is gone), a drawbridge (Kota Intan Bridge), and the port (Sunda Kelapa) with historic wooden schooners. The area is popular for street performers, food stalls, and bike rentals. It\'s best visited on weekends when the square is lively and car-free. The area is a glimpse into Jakarta\'s colonial past.', 'localisation' => '-6.1300, 106.8100', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1518548419970-58e3b4079ab2?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Yogyakarta (id: 57)
            ['city_id' => 57, 'name' => 'Borobudur', 'description' => 'Borobudur is a 9th-century Mahayana Buddhist temple in Central Java, Indonesia, one of the world\'s largest and most magnificent Buddhist monuments. It is a UNESCO World Heritage site and one of the New7Wonders of the World. The temple was built between 778 and 850 CE under the Sailendra dynasty and was abandoned in the 14th century (possibly due to volcanic eruptions). It was rediscovered in 1814 and restored in the 1970s-1980s. The temple is built in the shape of a mandala (a cosmic diagram), with a base (representing the world of desire), five square terraces (representing the world of form), three circular terraces (representing the world of formlessness), and a central stupa at the top (representing enlightenment). The temple has 2,672 relief panels (the world\'s largest collection of Buddhist reliefs) and 504 Buddha statues. The journey to the top symbolizes the path to enlightenment. The best time to visit is at sunrise (a popular tour) for the stunning views and softer light. The temple is also beautiful at sunset. Visitors must wear a sarong (provided). Borobudur is a spiritual and architectural masterpiece, a must-see for any visitor to Java.', 'localisation' => '-7.6079, 110.2038', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1518548419970-58e3b4079ab2?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 57, 'name' => 'Prambanan', 'description' => 'Prambanan is a 9th-century Hindu temple compound in Central Java, Indonesia, dedicated to the Trimurti (the three main Hindu gods): Brahma (the creator), Vishnu (the preserver), and Shiva (the destroyer). It is a UNESCO World Heritage site and the largest Hindu temple complex in Indonesia. The temple was built between 850 and 900 CE by the Rakai Pikatan of the Mataram Kingdom and was abandoned in the 11th century (possibly due to earthquakes and volcanic eruptions). The complex originally had 240 temples, but many are now in ruins. The main temple is the Shiva temple (47 meters tall), with statues of Shiva, Durga (his consort), Ganesha (his son), and Agastya (his teacher). The Brahma temple (south) and Vishnu temple (north) are smaller. The temples are decorated with reliefs depicting the Ramayana epic (the story of Rama and Sita). The temple is also famous for the Ramayana Ballet performed at the open-air theater (with the temple as a backdrop). The best time to visit is late afternoon for the sunset and the ballet. Prambanan is a stunning example of Hindu architecture and a must-see in Yogyakarta.', 'localisation' => '-7.7520, 110.4914', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1518548419970-58e3b4079ab2?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 57, 'name' => 'Kraton Palace', 'description' => 'The Kraton Palace (Kraton Ngayogyakarta Hadiningrat) is the official palace of the Sultan of Yogyakarta, the only remaining monarchy in Indonesia recognized by the national government. The palace was built in 1755-1756 by Sultan Hamengkubuwono I, the founder of the Yogyakarta Sultanate. The palace is a complex of buildings, courtyards, pavilions, gardens, and museums, blending Javanese, Islamic, and European architecture. The palace is not just a residence but a cultural center, still used for traditional ceremonies, dances, music (gamelan), and batik-making. Highlights include the Bangsal Kencana (the Golden Pavilion, with intricate carvings and a metal roof), the Museum (with royal artifacts, including silver, jewelry, masks, and gamelan instruments), the Magangan (a large courtyard), the Prabayeksa (the waiting hall), and the Dhamar (a mosque). The palace is also famous for the heirlooms, including the royal carriage (Kereta Kencana). The palace is open to visitors, with a museum and guided tours. The best time to visit is in the morning to see the cultural performances (schedule varies). The Kraton is a living museum of Javanese culture and a symbol of Yogyakarta\'s identity.', 'localisation' => '-7.8050, 110.3600', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1518548419970-58e3b4079ab2?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // ==================== PORTUGAL (City IDs 58-60) ====================
            // Lisbon (id: 58)
            ['city_id' => 58, 'name' => 'Belém Tower', 'description' => 'Belém Tower (Torre de Belém) is a 16th-century fortified tower on the Tagus River in Lisbon, a UNESCO World Heritage site and a symbol of Portugal\'s Age of Discovery. The tower was built between 1514 and 1520 under King Manuel I, designed by Francisco de Arruda. It was built as a defense system for the Tagus River and as a ceremonial gateway to Lisbon. The tower is a masterpiece of Manueline architecture (Portuguese late Gothic), with ornate details inspired by maritime themes: ropes, armillary spheres (a symbol of King Manuel I), crosses of the Order of Christ (the Knights Templar), and natural motifs (coral, seaweed, and rhinoceros horns). The tower has a bastion (with cannons), a two-story tower, and a courtyard. Highlights include the Chapel (with a ribbed vault), the Royal Terrace (with a statue of the Virgin of Belém), the Governor\'s Room, the King\'s Room, the Audience Room, and the terrace with views of the river. The tower is small and can be crowded (long lines). The best time to visit is early morning. Belém Tower is a must-see for any visitor to Lisbon, symbolizing Portugal\'s maritime history and Manueline architecture.', 'localisation' => '38.6914, -9.2158', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516483638261-f4dbaf036963?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 58, 'name' => 'Jerónimos Monastery', 'description' => 'The Jerónimos Monastery (Mosteiro dos Jerónimos) is a 16th-century monastery in Belém, Lisbon, a UNESCO World Heritage site and one of Portugal\'s greatest architectural masterpieces. The monastery was built between 1501 and 1601 under King Manuel I, designed by Diogo de Boitaca and later João de Castilho. It was built to commemorate Vasco da Gama\'s voyage to India and to serve as a burial place for the House of Aviz (the royal family). The monastery is a masterpiece of Manueline architecture (Portuguese late Gothic), with intricate stone carvings of maritime themes (ropes, anchors, armillary spheres), natural motifs (coral, seaweed, oak leaves), and religious symbols (crosses of the Order of Christ). Highlights include the Church of Santa Maria (with a stunning nave with no pillars, and the tombs of Vasco da Gama and Luís de Camões), the Cloisters (two levels, with intricate arches and gargoyles), the Refectory (with a Manueline window), the Chapter House (with a vaulted ceiling), and the Museum of Archaeology (with artifacts from Portugal\'s history). The monastery is large and impressive; allow at least 1-2 hours. The monastery is located next to the Belém Tower and the Belém Cultural Center.', 'localisation' => '38.6979, -9.2059', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516483638261-f4dbaf036963?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 58, 'name' => 'São Jorge Castle', 'description' => 'São Jorge Castle (Castelo de São Jorge) is a Moorish castle located on a hilltop in the Alfama district of Lisbon, offering stunning panoramic views of the city, the Tagus River, and the 25 de Abril Bridge. The site has been fortified since the 8th century BCE, but the current castle was built by the Moors in the 11th century. It was conquered by King Afonso Henriques (Portugal\'s first king) in 1147. The castle served as a royal palace, military barracks, and prison. Highlights include the main gate (with a drawbridge), the castle walls (with 11 towers, you can walk on them), the courtyard (with cannons), the Archaeological Site (with ruins of a 7th-century BCE settlement and Moorish houses), the Camera Obscura (a periscope-like device projecting live views of the city, requires a separate ticket), the Ulysses Tower (with a museum on Lisbon\'s history), the garden (with peacocks), and the cafe. The views are spectacular, especially at sunset. The castle is at the top of a steep hill, but escalators and elevators are available from the Pombaline Downtown. The castle is a popular attraction and can be crowded; visit early morning or late afternoon.', 'localisation' => '38.7139, -9.1334', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516483638261-f4dbaf036963?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Algarve (id: 59)
            ['city_id' => 59, 'name' => 'Benagil Sea Cave', 'description' => 'The Benagil Sea Cave (Algar de Benagil) is one of the most famous natural attractions in the Algarve, a spectacular sea cave with a natural skylight. The cave is located near the village of Benagil, between Praia de Benagil and Praia da Marinha. The cave has a large dome-shaped chamber with a hole in the ceiling (the skylight), allowing sunlight to create a beautiful glow. The cave also has a small sandy beach inside. The cave is only accessible by water (by kayak, stand-up paddleboard, or small boat). Kayaking is the most popular option (you can kayak through the arch into the cave), but it requires physical effort and is only possible in calm conditions (avoid windy days). Boat tours (from Benagil beach or from nearby towns like Portimão, Albufeira, or Lagos) offer a quicker, easier way to see the cave (you can\'t get off the boat, but you can see the cave from the water). The cave is very popular, with long lines. The best time to visit is early morning (to avoid crowds and get the best light) or late afternoon. The cave is a must-see for any visitor to the Algarve, one of the most photographed spots in Portugal.', 'localisation' => '37.0900, -8.4200', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516483638261-f4dbaf036963?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 59, 'name' => 'Ponta da Piedade', 'description' => 'Ponta da Piedade is a dramatic headland on the southern coast of the Algarve, near Lagos, famous for its stunning golden sandstone cliffs, rock formations, arches, sea stacks, grottoes, and hidden beaches. The area is a geological wonder, shaped by erosion over millions of years. The views from the top of the cliffs are spectacular, especially at sunrise and sunset. Visitors can walk along the boardwalks and stairs, offering different viewpoints. For a closer look, visitors can take a boat tour (from Lagos Marina or Ponta da Piedade, 30-60 minutes), kayak, or stand-up paddleboard through the arches and into the caves. The water is clear and turquoise, excellent for snorkeling. The area is also popular for rock climbing and fishing. The name "Ponta da Piedade" means "Point of Mercy" in Portuguese, possibly referring to the dangerous currents (many shipwrecks). The area is part of the Parque Natural da Ria Formosa. Ponta da Piedade is a must-see for its natural beauty, one of the most photogenic spots in the Algarve. The best time to visit is late afternoon for the golden light on the cliffs.', 'localisation' => '37.0800, -8.6700', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516483638261-f4dbaf036963?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 59, 'name' => 'Ria Formosa', 'description' => 'Ria Formosa is a stunning lagoon system and natural park on the Algarve coast, stretching 60 kilometers from Ancão to Manta Rota. It is a protected area (Parque Natural da Ria Formosa) known for its barrier islands, sand dunes, salt marshes, tidal flats, and lagoons. The park is home to diverse wildlife, including hundreds of bird species (flamingos, spoonbills, avocets, storks, herons), fish, shellfish (clams, oysters), and plants. The park is an important stopover for migratory birds. Activities include boat tours (from Olhão, Faro, or Tavira, visiting the barrier islands, such as Ilha Deserta (Barreta Island), Ilha da Culatra, and Ilha de Tavira, with beautiful sandy beaches), birdwatching (with hides), kayaking (through the channels), cycling (along the Ecovia do Litoral), and fishing. The park is also known for its traditional fishing communities (like the village of Cacela Velha) and seafood (especially clams, oysters, and octopus). The Ria Formosa is a beautiful, peaceful escape from the crowded beaches of the Algarve, offering a different perspective on the region. The best time to visit is spring and autumn for bird migration, and summer for the beaches.', 'localisation' => '37.0200, -7.9300', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516483638261-f4dbaf036963?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            
            // Porto (id: 60)
            ['city_id' => 60, 'name' => 'Dom Luís I Bridge', 'description' => 'The Dom Luís I Bridge (Ponte Dom Luís I) is a double-deck iron arch bridge that spans the Douro River between Porto and Vila Nova de Gaia. The bridge was designed by a student of Gustave Eiffel, Théophile Seyrig, and was completed in 1886. The bridge is 385 meters long, 8 meters wide, and has an arch span of 172 meters (one of the longest in the world at the time). The upper deck is for the Porto Metro (trams) and pedestrians, offering spectacular views of the Douro River, Porto\'s historic center (Ribeira), the Port wine cellars in Gaia, and the Douro Valley. The lower deck is for road traffic and pedestrians. The bridge is an icon of Porto and a symbol of the city. The best time to visit is at sunset, when the light creates beautiful reflections on the river and the bridge is illuminated. Visitors can walk across the upper deck (free), or take the metro (from São Bento to Jardim do Morro). The view from the Jardim do Morro park in Gaia is one of the best views of Porto. The bridge is especially beautiful at night when lit. The Dom Luís I Bridge is a must-see for any visitor to Porto, offering stunning views and a sense of history.', 'localisation' => '41.1400, -8.6100', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516483638261-f4dbaf036963?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 60, 'name' => 'Livraria Lello', 'description' => 'Livraria Lello is one of the most beautiful bookstores in the world, located in Porto, Portugal. The bookstore was opened in 1906 by the Lello brothers and is famous for its stunning Neo-Gothic and Art Nouveau architecture. The highlight is the magnificent curved red staircase, which inspired the moving staircases in the Harry Potter films (author J.K. Rowling lived in Porto in the 1990s and was a frequent visitor). The bookstore also features a stunning stained glass ceiling (with the motto "Decus in Labore" - "Dignity in Work"), intricate wood carvings, a facade with two painted figures representing Science and Art, and a skylight. The bookstore is still an operating bookstore (selling books in Portuguese, English, and other languages), but it has become a major tourist attraction, with long lines (sometimes hours). Entry is only with a ticket (5 euros, which is deductible from purchases). The best time to visit is early morning (just after opening) or late afternoon to avoid crowds. The bookstore is small and can be crowded, so it\'s not a quiet place to browse. However, the architecture is worth seeing. Livraria Lello is a must-see for Harry Potter fans and architecture lovers.', 'localisation' => '41.1465, -8.6151', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516483638261-f4dbaf036963?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
            ['city_id' => 60, 'name' => 'Porto Wine Cellars', 'description' => 'The Porto Wine Cellars (Caves do Vinho do Porto) are located in Vila Nova de Gaia, across the Douro River from Porto, where the Port wine is aged in barrels before being bottled. Port is a fortified wine (brandy is added to stop fermentation, leaving residual sugar) produced in the Douro Valley (a UNESCO World Heritage site). The wine cellars are located in Gaia because the climate is cooler and more humid than the Douro Valley, better for aging. There are over 50 port wine cellars, with many offering guided tours and tastings. The most famous include Taylor\'s (founded 1692, with a museum, a tasting room, and a restaurant with views), Graham\'s (founded 1820, with a lodge on a hilltop, a tasting room, and a restaurant), Sandeman (founded 1790, with a museum and the iconic "Don" logo), Cálem (with a guided tour and fado music), and Ferreira (with a museum and a tasting of Dona Antónia, the first woman in the port industry). Tours typically explain the history of port, the production process (including the types of port: ruby, tawny, white, late bottled vintage (LBV), and vintage), and end with a tasting of 2-3 wines. Allow 1-2 hours per cellar. The best time to visit is in the morning to avoid crowds. The views of Porto from Gaia are spectacular.', 'localisation' => '41.1300, -8.6100', 'image' => 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516483638261-f4dbaf036963?w=800', 'created_at' => now(), 'updated_at' => now()],
        ];

